(1, 'Commit to Running Your Business with Your Eyes Wide Open', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p>â€œFace new challenges, seize new opportunities, test your resources against the unknown and, in the process, discover your own unique potential.â€   \r\n~John Amatt ~</p>\r\n<p>Itâ€™s Januaryâ€”time for New Year resolutions and goal setting.  Congratulations to you if youâ€™ve already established your 2012 business goals.  The first step to success has been completedâ€”youâ€™ve documented your metrics.  However, have you determined your plan of attack?  Are you aware of your companyâ€™s real strengths, what sets you apart from your competitors and which opportunities will get you the biggest bang for your buck? </p>  \r\n<p>Take some time to assess your current situation and critique your competitive abilities to meet customer needs in the marketplace.   Strategists and marketers alike, refer to this process as a SWOT.  At first glance for many small businesses, this seems like an onerous task that is difficult to complete with the daily pressures of keeping the business going.  However, a SWOT Analysis is a powerful technique for understanding your strengths and weaknesses, and for looking at the opportunities and threats you face.  It can help you carve a sustainable niche in your market.</p>\r\n<p>What makes SWOT particularly powerful is that, with a little thought, it can help you uncover opportunities that you are well positioned to exploit. And by understanding the weaknesses of your business, you can manage and eliminate threats that would otherwise catch you unaware.</p>\r\n<p>More than this, by looking at your firm and your competitors using the SWOT framework, you can start to craft a strategy that helps you distinguish yourself from your competitors, so that you can compete successfully in your market. </p>\r\n<p>When completing a SWOT itâ€™s important to remember that strengths and weaknesses are often internal to your organization. Opportunities and threats often relate to external factors. </p>\r\n<p><b>Strengths:</b></p> \r\n<p>What advantages does your company have? </p> \r\nWhat do you do better than anyone else? </p> \r\nWhat unique or lowest-cost resources do you have access to?</p>\r\nWhat do people in your market see as your strengths? </p> \r\nWhat factors mean that you â€œget the saleâ€? </p> \r\n<p>Consider this from an internal perspective, and from the point of view of your customers and people in your market.</p>\r\n<p>In looking at your strengths, think about them in relation to your competitors â€“ for example, if all your competitors provide quick turnaround, the a speedy delivery process is not a strength in the market, it is a necessity. </p>\r\n<p><b>Weaknesses:</b></p>\r\n<p>What could you improve? </p> \r\n<p>What should you avoid? </p> \r\n<p>What are people in your market likely to see as weaknesses? </p> \r\n<p>What factors lose you sales? </p> \r\n<p>Again, consider this from an internal and external basis: Do other people seem to perceive weaknesses that you do not see? Are your competitors doing any better than you? It is best to be realistic now, and face any unpleasant truths as soon as possible. </p>\r\n<p><b>Opportunities:</b></p>\r\n<p>Where are the good opportunities facing you? </p> \r\n<p>What are the interesting trends you are aware of? </p> \r\n<p>Useful opportunities can come from such things as:</p>\r\n<p>Changes in technology and markets on both a broad and narrow scale</p> \r\n<p>Changes in government policy related to your field</p> \r\n<p>Changes in social patterns, population profiles, lifestyle changes, etc.</p> \r\n<p>Local events</p> \r\n<p>A useful approach for looking at opportunities is to look at your strengths and ask yourself whether these open up any opportunities.</p>\r\n<p>Alternatively, look at your weaknesses and ask yourself whether you could create opportunities by eliminating them.</p>\r\n<p><b>Threats:</b></p> \r\n<p>What obstacles do you face? </p> \r\n<p>What is your competition doing that you should be worried about? </p> \r\n<p>Are the required specifications for your products or services changing? </p> \r\n<p>Is changing technology threatening your position? </p> \r\n<p>Do you have bad debt or cash-flow problems? </p> \r\n<p>Could any of your weaknesses seriously threaten your business? </p> \r\n<p>Carrying out this analysis will often be illuminating â€“ both in terms of pointing out what needs to be done, and in putting problems into perspective. You can also apply SWOT Analysis to your competitors. As you do this, youâ€™ll start to see how and where you should compete against them.</p>\r\n<p>For a worksheet that you can use to help facilitate your SWOT planning session, visit the Articles page in the Tips & Tools section of the Business Accelerator website, or paste this URL into your browser: https://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/tips-and-tools/white-papers/index.php </p>\r\n<p>Finally, here are some handy tips that I have found to make SWOTs more productive. </p>\r\n<p>Only accept precise, verifiable statements (â€œCustomer savings of $10 per sq. footâ€, rather than â€œGood value for moneyâ€). </p> \r\n<p>Ruthlessly prune long lists of factors, and prioritize factors so that you spend your time thinking about the most significant factors. </p> \r\n<p>Make sure that options generated are carried through to later stages in the strategy formation process. </p> \r\n<p>Apply SWOT at the right level â€“ for example, at product or product line level, rather than at the much vaguer whole company level. Unless you are a start-up company or a relatively small company with a single product or service offering. </p> \r\n<p>While the year is still young, schedule your SWOT planning session on the calendar.  Invite all your team members that deal directly with customers or ones that understand your offerings completely.  Start the New Year with your eyes open in regards to your companyâ€™s strategic direction. </p>\r\n<p>\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.\r\n  </p>\r\n', '', '', '2012-01-12', '2012-02-23 19:05:33'),
(2, 'Tips for Leveraging Inbound Marketing', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach; CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p>â€Build it and they will come." from <i>Field of Dreams</i></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thereâ€™s no doubt that business to business marketers still need to deploy traditional outbound marketing such as cold calling, networking and direct mail to meet their revenue goals.  However, inbound marketing, coined by the company HubSpot, is not to be skipped in todayâ€™s digital world.</p>  \r\n<p>Inbound marketing is defined as the marketing strategy that focuses on getting found by customers.  Your website, blog and social networking activities are key components of this strategy. They should have significant resource allocated to them in order to amplify your presence and credibility, as well as generate leads in your market space.  Here are two goals to keep your inbound marketing on track: </p>\r\n<p><b>Goal #1: Build Website Traffic & Get Found by Your Sales Prospects</b></p>\r\n<p>You know the saying, â€œBuild It and They Will Come.â€  Well, thanks to the Internetâ€™s search engines, this is somewhat true . . . as long as you are writing your web content using the right keywords, the Holy Grail of online marketing.    Once you learn what words and phrases your customers use and where they use them, you can seek out and engage the people you want to reach.  Search engine optimization on each of your web pages, your blog, social network postings, and your articles should be a priority so that Google is working for you even when your business is closed.  For web pages, be sure to continuously update and add â€œsearch engine optimizedâ€ content, i.e., content with your selected keywords.  Search engines regularly look for updates so keep the fresh stuff coming!</p>\r\n<p>Content truly is king in todayâ€™s information-rich world.  Having valuable content thatâ€™s posted on the Internet and promoted via social media venues is key to being found by your prospect.  Not only do well written articles help you get found and contribute to your search engine optimization strategy, they also work well to engage prospects initially . . . opening up the relationship between your company and them.  Keep most of your content in your blog.  By adding new content regularly to your blog, youâ€™ll increase your Google page rankings.  Furthermore, the more your audience trusts you and the information provided to them, the better your chances of earning their business.</p>\r\n<p>Support your search engine optimization efforts with link building.  Use your relationships with the media, suppliers, social networking platforms, and bloggers to create instant connections between their site and yours.  In short, the more appropriate links there are to a page of content, the greater the likelihood of that page being accessed by a visitor and search engine crawler.</p> \r\n<p><b>Goal #2:  Convert Prospects into Sales Leads</b></p>\r\n<p>Be sure to include a call to action to remind your prospect what you want them to do once theyâ€™ve absorbed all your new content.  Your goal and the type of campaign youâ€™re running will determine the type of call to action you want to use.  You might use buttons that say things like â€œClick Here to Learn Moreâ€ or â€œDownload This White Paper Nowâ€ to move your prospect to action, such as registering with an email or phone number.  Once you have this information, you can continue with outbound marketing techniques such as telemarketing, direct mail, or email to develop the lead.</p> \r\n<p>Your landing page, the web page in which prospects land after clicking on a call to action, is critical to converting visitors into prospects.  Well written landing pages will focus on benefits, not your capabilities or capacities.  Know your prospect and speak about his pains and challengesâ€”highlight â€œwhatâ€™s in it for himâ€ and express a strong differentiation of your company from your competition. In addition, from a measurement perspective, landing pages can help you determine the success of a particular campaign because youâ€™ll be able to track the number of visitors and their source.</p>\r\n<p>When determining your marketing plan for this year, be sure to allocate resources to your inbound marketing strategy.  Solicit advice and counsel from an expert tactician to make sure your strategy is on-target.  If financial resources are tight, consider employing interns to help you implement.  Donâ€™t miss being found by your prospects because your budget is tight or your people too few.</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p><p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>\r\n', '', '', '2012-02-14', '2012-02-23 19:02:25'),
(5, 'Three Key Habits Your Small Business Needs to Adopt for Success', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Sales Coach, CEO, Wright Business Institute', '<p> "My success, part of it certainly, is that I have focused in on a few things." â€” Bill Gates\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p>My wife and business partner met a business turn-around expert on a flight and asked him about his formula for business success. â€œPhooey!â€ he replied. My wife, clearly thinking she had misheard, responded with, â€œNo, seriously, how do you do it?â€ He chuckled and then went on to describe the acronym that had spelled success for any company he had ever turned around: F. U. E. â€“ Focus, Urgency, and Execution. </p>\r\n<p>Having coached thousands of small business owners I couldnâ€™t agree more that these are the three primary habits any small business should adopt if they are serious about success. </p>\r\n<p><b>Focus:</b> Every small business owner and employee wears multiple hats. The nature of a small business also means that you experiment as you continually refine your business model to meet changing market demands. But this small business reality does not give you permission to abandon your focus. You need to have a primary focus around which the company is aligned at any point in time. It should be as clear for each of your employees as it is for you. If itâ€™s not, then itâ€™s your job as a small business owner to determine and communicate itâ€”not once, but in an ongoing way that your employees and you have a rallying point around which you are orienting at any given time.</p>\r\n<p><b> Urgency:</b> For your small business to be successfully urgent, you need to start telling the truth about your busy-ness. It is very easy to appear urgent as you hustle about your day with a full calendar and an overwhelming to do list. But real urgency builds on focus. You are urgent about the things that really matter and you self-impose requirements to deliver things quickly. Think about how you operate before going on vacation. You know youâ€™ll be in less communication for the week and your mindset and motivation responds in kind. You get your desk flat and have things handled at a certain level so that you can let go. But what if the end of each week was like the day before vacation. What would get accomplished? </p>\r\n<p><b>Execution: </b> All the focus and urgency in the world means little if you never follow through on what your plan is. This year, do you intend to create a sales culture, achieve an aggressive revenue goal, or launch a new product? Whatever you choose for your focus, your main touch point each week should be â€“ how am I doing on execution. Otherwise, itâ€™s just another good idea. </p>\r\n<p>This week, adopt FUE as an assignment for yourself and your team. Come to agreement on your focus and see how you can use urgency to drive through to execution. You may be surprised by what you can accomplish.</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p><p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>\r\n  </p>', '', '', '2012-02-28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(6, 'Do Not Leave Profitability up to Chance . . . TARGET', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p> â€œIf your goal is anything but profitability - if it''s to be big, or to grow fast, or to become a technology leader - you''ll hit problems.â€ Michael Porter </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Now more than ever, it is critical to make sure that you are focused on profitability. Many small business owners are lured into thinking that the right customers are defined as â€œanyone with money.â€  This is a fatal mistake. We all know that it is not possible to be all things to all peopleâ€”itâ€™s not realistic and itâ€™s certainly not profitable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Targeting is one tool that allows you to keep your eye on profitability both with your existing customers and with potential ones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hereâ€™s the key reason why targeting is a do-or-die proposition during challenging economic times: <i>It is the profitable customers who will sustain you and build your business.  You must understand the make-up of your profitable customers so you can determine the profile of the new customers you should acquire.</i></p> \r\n<p>Acquisition of new clients is expensive enough; during rough times <b>you canâ€™t afford to acquire new clients who will drain your profitability</b>.  Nailing down the type of customer who infuses profit into your business is the first step to using your marketing dollars wisely.</p>\r\n<p>A few years ago, I had the pleasure to work with Michael Walsh, President of Kaizen Consulting Services.  He suggests using the following steps to understand the profitability of your customers:</p>\r\n<p>~Sort your customer base by Gross Sales (highest to lowest) and then create another sort by Gross Profit.\r\n<p>~Now take your Gross Sales sort and divide it into 5 equal groups or quintiles.  To know what a quintile is equal to, take your total Gross Sales and divide it by 5.\r\n<p>~Break out your Gross Profit sort into quintiles too.\r\n<p>~Study the customers in the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd quintiles on both sorts. \r\n<ul><li>Are they the same customers for both Gross Profit and Gross Sales?</li><li>What kind of effort goes into supporting a profitable customer versus an unprofitable one?</li><li>Whatâ€™s the profile of profitable clients?  What industry are they in and what size are they?  What products do they buy?  Is there a common decision-making process?  Do you see a common thread across the group on how they buy?</li></ul>\r\n<p>The results of this analysis will give you the tools you need to determine what your â€œbest potentialâ€ new customers should look like.  As an added bonus, youâ€™ll have a list of your most profitable customers.  Take the necessary steps to strengthen your relationships with them, ensuring future sales and referrals.</p>\r\n<p>This week, work with your accountant or bookkeeper to do a customer analysis sorted by sales and sorted by profit.  If profit data isnâ€™t handy, then do a shortened analysis.  Take your clients in your 1st and 2nd quintiles and estimate their profitability; assign each a ratingâ€”1, 2, or 3 with 1 being highly profitable, 3 being hardly profitable.  Do you see a trend?  Are there distinct characteristics differences between your highly profitable and your hardly profitable?  If so, take note . . . now youâ€™ve got your target.</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>\r\n  </p>\r\n', '', '', '2012-01-24', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(7, 'The Difficult Conversation', 'Dr. Bob Wright CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p>â€œIt is not because things are difficult that we do not dare, it is because we do not dare that things are difficult.â€  --Seneca</p>\r\n                      \r\n\r\n<p>If you have a difficult conversation you have been avoiding, chances are you need to shift your context. Perhaps you need to tell someone they are falling short or you are unhappy about their behavior.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Difficult conversations are most successful when you establish the context of a win/win situation. The other person needs to know that you have their best interest at heart and you can start that by sharing your vision for them. What do you see for them? What do you want? If you donâ€™t have a vision for them, then the impetus is on you to step back and think about that before you meet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Difficult conversations can be a gift to the receiver. You may be taking a risk by telling them something no one else has been willing to. Chances are that your feedback will further their personal development, but others havenâ€™t cared enough to risk with them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, pick a difficult conversation that you can take onâ€”whether itâ€™s a customer, employee, prospect, or manager. Set a time that you will meet with them so that you can no longer avoid it. Spend a few minutes thinking about your vision for the person and then follow through. Starting the conversation can be very simple. â€œJohn, Iâ€™ve been avoiding giving you some feedback and I want to do that now but first let me tell you why this matters. Hereâ€™s what I see for youâ€¦.â€ Again, the words arenâ€™t as important as the intention. Are you coming from a space of win/win? If so, your message will be received.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>\r\n\r\n', '', '', '2011-12-01', '2012-02-23 19:12:01'),
(8, 'Three Ways to Know What Your Business Is Worth', 'Rich Lyons, CEO, Lyons Consulting Group; Finance and Growth Coach', '<p>â€œA nickel ain''t worth a dime anymore.â€ --Yogi Berra</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I love helping entrepreneurs build beautiful businesses in which they would love to grow old and retire.  Whether you are building your business to live in or to sell, it is critically important to understand what your business is worth. There are 3 primary ways to assess value of a business.</p> \r\n\r\n<p>Multiple of Profit</p>\r\n<p>The first way to assess is as a multiple of your bottom line. For many businesses, four times profits is a fair price formula. Depending on the industry and the desirability of the company, it may be able to assess at ten to twelve times profits. You are likely to know if you are in one of these highly desirable sectors. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Percentage of Revenue</p>\r\n<p>Another way to evaluate a business is by using a percentage of revenue. This method is fairly common in service industries. In fact, it is not uncommon to see a service business sell for anything between 40 percent and 125 percent of revenue depending on the solidity of the customer base and the likelihood of customers transferring to the new owner. </p>  \r\n\r\n<p>Book Value</p>\r\n<p>Still a third way to appraise a business is book value. Book value would be receivables and the value of all assets minus debts and payables. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can set goals for yourself on your target value for your business and decide how much youâ€™d like your business to be worth. More often than not, calculating your businessâ€™ value ensures that you are being realistic and not kidding yourself. Often people begin imagining that their business is worth more than it truly is. People I have coached have imagined that their business is worth several hundred thousand dollars when, in fact, it was only worth forty to sixty thousand dollars at the moment. </p>  \r\n\r\n<p>Make no mistake. There may be other variables in the equation â€“ products, services, and processes that maybe unique to you and increase your companyâ€™s value-- but remember most sellers overestimate the price of their businesses and thereâ€™s no replacement for a good appraisal to give you an idea of where you stand. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, do an honest assessment of your companyâ€™s value. You can use one, or all three, of the methods, listed above. Then set a goal for yourself related to growing the value of the company in 2012. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted. </p>\r\n', '', '', '2011-12-08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(9, 'What Color Is Your "Buyer/Seller" Brain Color?', 'Sheila Glazov, Personality Expert, Speaker, Author', '<p>Do you ever feel like you are closing doors instead of deals? </p>\r\n<p>Do you wonder why you dread making sales calls to some customers and are delighted to contact others? </p>\r\n<p>The answers to these questions are easy once you discover your and your customers&rsquo; Brain Color personalities. <strong>The</strong><strong> What Color&nbsp;is Your Brain?&reg;</strong><strong> concept is a</strong><span class="intro1"> fun and fascinating approach</span>, which simplifies the complex puzzle of your personality traits and talents. </p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yellow Brain Sales Professionals are: Dedicated, Organized, and Loyal</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Blue Brain Sales Professionals are: Helpful, Creative, and Communicative</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Green Brain Sales Professionals are: Efficient, Logical, and Technically Skillful </p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Orange Brain Sales Professional are: Competitive, Resourceful, and Results Oriented</p>\r\n<p>To be a successful sales professional, it is critical to understand your buyer&rsquo;s &ldquo;Brain Color Point Of View&rdquo;, tailor your sales presentation and calls to your buyer&rsquo;s &ldquo;Brain Color&rdquo; personality, and recognize how:</p>\r\n<p>1.&nbsp; Their personality influences the way they respond to you, your product, and/or your service.</p>\r\n<p>2. &nbsp;You can deal with their purchasing concerns during your sales presentation. </p>\r\n<p>3. &nbsp;To help them make decisions about solutions or services that serve them best.</p>\r\n<p>4. &nbsp;They receive information about your product or service. </p>\r\n<p>5. &nbsp;Your customers are motivated to purchase what you are selling.</p>\r\n<p>The following are &ldquo;Brain Color Sales Tips&rdquo; to help you communicate and build rapport with your customer when making a sales call and presentation.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Yellow Brainers</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Be polite and punctual</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Respect their personal values of organization and rules</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stay on track</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tell them all the details</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Encourage them to talk about their achievements</p>\r\n<p><strong>Blue Brainers</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Show your sincerity</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Respect their emotions</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use stories to explain your point</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Connect with them personally</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Encourage them to talk about their family</p>\r\n<p><strong>Green Brainers</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Don&rsquo;t make small talk</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Respect their privacy</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Be brief, but informative</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Give them lots of statistics and data</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Encourage them to talk about their knowledge, not yours</p>\r\n<p><strong>Orange Brainers</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Be direct</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Respect their spontaneity</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Make your point quickly</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Give them the results, not facts and figures</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Encourage them to talk about their hobbies or vacations</p>\r\n<p>To close the sale, it also is essential to understand what motivates the different Brain Color customers to buy whatever you are selling. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Yellow Brainer Motivators</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Doing what is right</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Completing tasks </p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Meeting deadlines</p>\r\n<p><strong>Blue Brainer Motivators</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Valuing their ideas</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Opportunities to share their feelings</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sharing creative opportunities</p>\r\n<p><strong>Green Brainer Motivators</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Problem-solving opportunities</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Creating a system or procedure</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cutting-edge resources</p>\r\n<p><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Orange Brainer Motivators</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Financial rewards</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Rapid results&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The excitement of change</p>\r\n<p>Now you have the knowledge to easily recognize your and your customers&rsquo; &ldquo;Brain Color&rdquo; personalities. You will find it easier to quickly increase your sales by listening, connecting, and selling with your &ldquo;Brain Color&rdquo; skills. This information will also enable you to communicate clearly, which will help your customers unmistakably hear and understand what you mean to say during your sales calls and presentations. </p>\r\n<p><strong>The Dreaded Task</strong></p>\r\n<p>I found the task that I had dreaded so</p>\r\n<p>Was not so difficult when one begun;</p>\r\n<p>It was the dread itself that was the foe, </p>\r\n<p>And dread once conquered means a victory won!</p>\r\n<p><em>Margaret E. Bruner</em></p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.&nbsp; Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>\r\n<p>Sheila N. Glazov presented the &ldquo;Sell More - What Color Is Your Brain?&reg;&rdquo; program at the Business Accelerator Fall Symposium on October 5th. Sheila is an internationally known <strong>&ldquo;Green Brain&rdquo;</strong> personality expert, <strong>&ldquo;Yellow Brain&rdquo;</strong> award-winning author, <strong>&ldquo;Orange Brain&rdquo;</strong><strong> </strong>engaging professional speaker and <strong>&ldquo;Blue Brain&rdquo;</strong> passionate educator. To learn more about Sheila&rsquo;s programs and books, visit her website <a href="http://www.sheilaglazov.com/">www.sheilaglazov.com</a>. &nbsp;</p>', '', '', '2011-11-09', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10, 'Hey Baby Whats Your Sign - What Works and Doesnt Work in Starting a Good Conversation', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute Sales Coach', '<p align="center">"It was impossible to get a conversation going;everybody was talking too much." -Yogi Berra</p>\r\n<p>You have identified a good networking opportunity, you have geared yourself up to uncover some leads, you are face to face with a cold call prospect and . . . now what? Starting a conversation may seem obvious and basic, but the truth of the matter is that even seasoned professionals tend to drop the ball in this critical arena. They may not ask someone what their sign is, but they do the sales professional equivalent by going about their pitch without giving it a second thought. So how do you do it differently?</p> \r\n\r\n<p>First, you need to recognize that starting a conversation is often the most difficult part of engaging with someone. Just the simple awareness will help you have a sense of humor and compassion and give you permission to practice and learn a skill that you may think you should already have mastered.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second, effective conversation starters are best delivered with genuine interest, interest in what the other person wants in the situation when you are meeting them and a genuine investment in seeing that they get it. Say you meet someone at a conference. Find out how the conference is going for them. What are they there for and how are they doing at getting that. Or find out how things are generally going for them at work and what you can do to generate value for them. The more you invest in others, the more they will be interested in investing in you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are afraid that this "approach" will come off as fake or not genuine, you need to remember that every one of us has within us an innate curiosity. When we are little kids, we are curious about the world and how things work and what people are doing and why. Think of the two-year old who is constantly asking, "why?" Our socialization as we grow up is what shuts down our curiosity. But the good news is that our sales goals are a great opportunity to reawaken this innate desire to learn, to know, and to contribute to others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, exercise your conversation-starting muscle. Discover the other people in your life by moving them from a faceless prospect to a real human being. Let yourself be curious about who they are and what they want. Use the week to experiment with getting to know people and give yourself permission to make mistakes. You may discover that by dropping your typical pitch, youâ€™ll actually pick up more sales in the long run.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-02-15', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(11, 'Backyard Networking! Approaching Friends and Neighbors for Leads', 'By Dr. Bob WrightCEO, Wright Business InstituteSales Coach', '<p align="center">"We cannot live only for ourselves. A thousand fibers connect us with our fellow men."</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Herman Melville~</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whether you&rsquo;re grilling out, raking leaves, or just saying hello, your backyard, front yard or neighborhood party could be a great, untapped source of leads for your business. And yet we&rsquo;ve all been in the position of avoiding "that friend" or "that neighbor" who does nothing but push his or her business. So how do you get leads without driving people away?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Simple. You serve. Find out what others do and what they need, then help them out in any way you can. And don&rsquo;t limit your service to their business. Maybe they are looking for a dentist for their kids or a job referral for a friend &ndash; it doesn&rsquo;t really matter. What matters is that you care about and invest in them. If you&rsquo;re like most people, this habit may be new to you at this level. You may talk to friends or neighbors, but do you seek to help them solve their problems or achieve their life goals on a regular basis? If not, you&rsquo;re missing out on an incredible depth and richness in your life, and you&rsquo;re leaving scores of leads on the table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How do you get started? Try an open-ended statement or question and let them talk. "Tell me about you. What&rsquo;s been going on?" Keep the conversation moving but don&rsquo;t get caught in advice giving. The more you can be a good active listener, the more they will feel supported by you. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>The more that you can seek to serve, the deeper your relationship, the more you are invested in them, and the more they are invested in you. You may find referrals simply coming your way as they seek to reciprocate or you may be more comfortable asking directly for referrals because you have served them so powerfully.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, pick one neighbor or friend you will target to serve and, by doing that, set-up a foundation for referrals. Engage them in a solid conversation and look to see how you can solve their problems. You&rsquo;ll be amazed at the business that comes your way!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.&nbsp; Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-10-13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(12, 'Test, Test More, and Test Again', 'Scott Cooper Principal, Marketing Engine Group Guest Webinar Presenter', '<p align="center">"How you gather, manage and use information will determine whether you win or lose."~Bill Gates~</p>\r\n<p><span class="apple-style-span">As small business owners, many times we&rsquo;re so excited to get our marketing piece out the door, it doesn&rsquo;t even cross our minds to slow down, do a little testing and see if our message or offer is on target.&nbsp; However, testing </span>completes a powerful loop of a Customer Relationship Marketing (CRM) program. You started with developing your database and capturing information about your customers. However, until you access that information and put it to use, your CRM program hasn''t really benefited the organization. The testing program allows you to put your customer knowledge to use in such a way as to establish your CRM program as a source for a continual learning culture within your organization. </p>\r\n<p><span class="apple-style-span">Remember to&nbsp;t</span>est, test more and then test again: Think of your customer base as a giant classroom, where you&rsquo;re the one learning. You can set up an effective testing program by:</p>\r\n<p>&middot;Taking a sample and trying something new versus another sample where you do nothing at all. Compare the results. Simple sample size calculators available on the Internet can help you determine the correct number to include in each sample and whether the results will hold up statistically.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;Taking two or three samples of customers from the same segment in your database (i.e., you can segment your customers by demographics, purchase behavior in terms of RFM &ndash; recency, frequency or monetary value of past purchases). Try something different in each and compare the results. </p>\r\n<p>What constitutes a test? A different promotional offer, sending out a newsletter on product trends or introduction of new services to one group but not another, size of envelope, frequency of e-mails, headlines, visuals, different merchandiseâ€¦really anything regarding what you&rsquo;re offering in terms of product, incentive, advice; how you&rsquo;re sending the information, where you&rsquo;re sending it, what it looks like, and how it&rsquo;s communicated. Then you simply track purchasing patterns over a set period of time to compare results.</p>\r\n<p>On your next marketing tactic, test different promotional ideas and analyze the results. Capture the findings, communicate them, and make them part of the ongoing business conversation within your building. By doing so, you''ll continually bring the customer to the decision making table. Companies that have their customers sitting at the virtual table through CRM inevitably stand the greatest chance of not only surviving but thriving!</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.&nbsp; Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-09-15', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(13, 'Two Old - Two New: Never Too Tough With LinkedIn', 'By Dean DeLisleCEO, Forward ProgressSocial Media Coach', '<p>"Social Media is about sociology and psychology more than technology."~ Brian Solis~</p>\r\n<p>Do you ever sign on to LinkedIn and not know what to do to generate some activity?  â€œTwo Old â€“ Two Newâ€ is an easy way to remember how you can create movement toward increased referrals and appointments.   Even on a busy day, a â€œsales-drivenâ€ business owner will manage to squeeze in four touches.  Thus, 2 + 2 or Two Old â€“ Two New will get you to those four dials.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>So what is it? Well itâ€™s simple and now even easier in LinkedIn. Go to your â€œContactsâ€ menu option and scroll through you connections. Then select the 2 oldest connections that you have not had a conversation with in quite some time. Now remember, like most, you probably have been adding many connections, from meetings, school, previous employment and other corners of your life. So find the 2 oldest and reach out for a meaningful conversation, to catch up, to be present.</p>\r\n<p>Now for the 2 new, you simply scan your connections and look for the 2 newest connections that you have not followed up with from recent networking events, business meetings, colleagues or any one of your connections. Even if you are the best sales person in the world, you will always miss people, I promise you! So scan your connections and find those 2 that youâ€™ve added and forgot to book meetings with or just lost steam in your effort. Then make your move to connect and have those meaningful conversations, be present and get the appointment.</p>\r\n<p>Now my promise is that if you do this everyday, yes everyday, 2 old â€“ 2 new, your weeks will be filled with referrals and appointments. Try it, take the 30 day challenge and tell us your story on our Business Accelerator LinkedIn Group. It hasnâ€™t missed yet!</p>\r\n<p><i>See you online â€“ Dean</i></p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-09-29', '2012-03-31 12:35:04'),
(14, 'Expand Your Staff, Not Your Overhead', 'Rich LyonsCEO, Lyons Consulting GroupFinance and Growth Coach', '<p>"Life is trying things to see if they work."~ Ray Bradbury ~</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So you need some hands to help build your business? If youâ€™re like most small business owners, there is always more work than resources and youâ€™re gun shy about committing to full-time, long-term staff. The good news? There are a variety of creative ways to expand your team without expanding your pocket book. As you look to grow, consider the value of interns and part-time employees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a small business, you are highly valuable to interns who need experience. A small business, by its very nature, means that you, and any interns you bring on, get to wear many hats. This ability to gain experience in a variety of roles gives an intern very high resume leverage. You are a gift to them not only in building their resume but also in helping them discover where their gifts and passions are. And you benefit by getting eager, motivated employees who either provide great project work in the short-term or whom you can screen for potential long-term employment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Similarly, your small business can be a valuable gift to part-timers. High quality part-time work is not always easy to find and can be absolutely invaluable to a parents or someone looking to job share. At the same time, you may be surprised to learn that two individuals job sharing have the potential to deliver one and a half times the value of a single employee for the same amount of hours. You may find that these part-timers become your lifelong employees because as you are ready to hire full-time employees, they may be in a position to transition as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, think about your personnel needs. What is not getting done that could be through an internship project? What invaluable tasks are getting dropped that could easily be handled by a regular, part-time employee? If you list anything in response to the two questions above, then consider placing a free job posting. You may find that you can easily expand your staff, without expanding your overhead.\r\nThe information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-08-03', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(15, 'Getting Past the Gatekeeper', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p>"If opportunity doesnâ€™t knock, build a door." ~Milton Berle~</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Getting past a gate keeper when youâ€™re making your dials can feel like a big waste of time and energy. You may have heard things like, "Iâ€™ll make sure they get your message," or "Email me your information and Iâ€™ll pass it along."</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Believe it or not, your biggest problem isnâ€™t any of these replies. Itâ€™s your incredibly misdirected goal. Rather than getting past the gatekeeper, you need to build a relationship by getting to know him or her.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gatekeepers are human beings and yet we treat them like a roadblock or an imposition. Really good gatekeepers are excellent employees, resources, managers, and networkers. If they effectively keep you out, then they also do a good job keeping the person they report to up and running, which makes them important people to know.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Imagine you are at a picnic, a party, or a networking event and a mutual friend introduces you to a gatekeeper. How would your conversation be different? Youâ€™d probably be excited to meet them. Youâ€™d be curious about who they are and what matters to them, what theyâ€™ve done, and where they are headed in life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, set a new goal for yourself. Get to know a gatekeeper from one of your prospects. Call them up but donâ€™t try to reach their boss. Instead, try to get to know them. You might even be direct about it and have some fun. Odds are that you will meet a really interesting person on the other end of the line and rather than becoming an enemy or a barrier, you may find yourself making a friend.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-08-17', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(16, 'Hiring A-Players', 'Rich Lyons, CEO, Lyons Consulting Group, Finance and Growth Coach', '<p>"If we weren''t still hiring great people and pushing ahead at full speed, it would be easy to fall behind and become a mediocre company."~Bill Gates~</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Are you looking to hire an A-team? If youâ€™re looking to staff up, donâ€™t sell yourself short. This is definitely an employerâ€™s market as there are a lot of great people looking for positions. There are also plenty of people looking to change careers who have terrific skills that would benefit your organization.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But as you build your team, how do you make sure you are hiring A-players? There are a couple of ways to ensure you hire the best. First, make sure you have a good filtering process in place. Your first level filter can be set up by making a clear request to which applicants need to respond. For example, if you ask for a resume and customized cover letter identifying three strengths and weaknesses, then you can rule out any resumes that come to you that donâ€™t meet your criteria; after all, an A-player follows instructions. Your second level filter could also be very basic, such as not accepting any resumes or cover letters with typos and any resumes that have career gaps where the individualâ€™s time is not accounted for. A-players check for typos and account for their time even if they spent it doing something unconventional.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second, you could consider some of the basic, and now automated, testing that is available. WonderlicÂ©  and similar companies offer a wide range of online tests that can give you information on anything from basic skills and aptitude to likelihood to succeed in customer service or sales. Again, these are not intended to be a definitive way to hire but a way to narrow the field. Youâ€™ll need to work with this kind of testing to see what parameters end up best suiting an individual who will succeed in your culture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Third, thoroughly explore your candidate during the interview. Individuals who have a track record of high performance are likely to continue that trend. Even past high school and collegiate achievements can be indicators. You can ask your prospect about the challenges and mistakes theyâ€™ve faced and how they dealt with and learned from them. A-players dig in deep, do the tough work, put themselves out there fully, make mistakes, can tell you where they have failed, and the lessons theyâ€™ve learned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What are some red flags that tell you youâ€™re not interviewing an A-player? They canâ€™t name a challenging situation. They describe an occurrence that doesnâ€™t appear challenging so they probably havenâ€™t dealt with much adversity in their lives. Or they canâ€™t tell you any mistakes theyâ€™ve made and what they learned from them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, pick one thing youâ€™ll implement in your hiring process that will help you uncover the high performers you want on your team. And remember, you have an A-level opportunity so donâ€™t settle for the B-team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-02-23', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
