(17, 'The Art of the Ask', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach ', '<p>"If there is something to gain and nothing to lose by asking, by all means ask!" ~W. Clement Stone~</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Looking for some high quality new customers? They are probably right in front of your face if youâ€™re willing to engage in the art of askingâ€¦for referrals that is.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Build your skills.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the most likely, and overlooked, ways of gaining high quality customers is by asking for a referral. But having the courage to consistently put yourself out there and ask is actually a skill to build. If youâ€™re just learning to ask for referrals, give yourself some grace and room to make mistakes. You may feel awkward and uncomfortable but the more you work the muscle, the better youâ€™ll get.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Give to get.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gracefully introducing the subject of a referral in such a way that people feel compelled to support you is the true art of the referral. Whether itâ€™s your customer or simply a friend, make sure that your request for a referral makes sense and flows from the conversation. This isnâ€™t about manipulation. The best way for you to have a referral naturally flow from the conversation is by making it your aim to serve the person as fully as you possibly can. Create value for them in the conversation by giving more than you ask for in return. You can help them by solving their challenges and introducing them to other resources. From the position of a giver, youâ€™ll find asking for referrals to be a natural outcome.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Push into new territory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maybe youâ€™ve naturally worked your muscle so that you dutifully ask for referrals. But even if youâ€™re a master at getting referrals, there is probably some new territory to explore. Push yourself to be a little more adventurous or daring in what youâ€™re asking for. Maybe your friend doesnâ€™t have a direct customer to refer you to but has a high power associate who might know someone. Be bold and ask. Be a little outrageous about what youâ€™re willing to ask for. Youâ€™ll be delighted to discover that some of the things you thought would be impossible suddenly become possible if youâ€™re only willing to ask.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week, ask for one referral each day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-02-14', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(18, 'What''s Working, What''s Not', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">&quot;Nobody counts the number of ads you run; they just remember the impression you make.&quot;~William Bernbach~</p>\r\n<p>Pfew! The campaign is out the door, a few responses are dribbling in and youâ€™ve got some appointments scheduled. Itâ€™s time to move on to the next marketing idea for your business.Â  Right?Â  Wrong.</p>\r\n<p>Now itâ€™s time to evaluate how your marketing program is performing against your stated objectives. Setting your objectives up front, before you start, is critical so that you can gauge whatâ€™s working and whatâ€™s not.Â  With this measurement data at your fingertips, you can begin to make adjustments with confidence.</p>\r\n<p>Once you know your objectives, you can establish how youâ€™re going to measure them. Leads are most effectively measured when you look at both lead quantity and lead quality. Additionally, response should be measured against costs to take into account the fact that marketing costs vary from one activity to another. Here are ways you can measure:</p>\r\n<ul type="disc">\r\n  <li><strong>Response Rates</strong>â€”an easy place to start but offers limited information</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Qualified Lead Rates</strong>â€”measures how many of your initial responses are qualified</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Order Rate</strong>â€”the best of all metrics because it tells you how many people actually bought; however, long sales cycles mean you wonâ€™t get this data for a long time, sometimes too long to be useful</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Cost per Response</strong>â€”adds marketing investment to the equation and is effective when comparing response from multiple media where costs vary widely</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Cost per Qualified Lead</strong>â€”useful when comparing performance of various lead sources; try to create a benchmark for cost per lead so youâ€™ll be able to measure the relative effectiveness of your different activities</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Cost per Order</strong>â€”this metric tells you whether you made any money on your first order</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Customer Acquisition Cost</strong>â€”very effective measurement that calculates both your marketing costs and your follow-up sales costs</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Lifetime Value per Customer</strong>â€”this is an essential metric if your &quot;front end&quot; marketing costs are higher than initial order revenue</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Conversion Rate</strong>â€”a useful metric that states how many visitors, leads, etc. actually convert to customers; commonly used in measuring the effectiveness of landing pages and other web pages in converting visitors into leads</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>For most small businesses, online marketing is orÂ <em>should be</em>Â a critical component of their lead generation efforts. Itâ€™s imperative that objectives are established upfront and tools such as Google Analytics are used to see how youâ€™re tracking against those objectives.</p>\r\n<p>Google Analytics is a fantastic, FREE online tool for small business owners. Your web designer can simply add it to your site and begin tracking things like: site traffic, entrance sources (how readers get to your site), exit pages (what pages readers are leaving your site from), keyword relevance, demographic information on your visitors, and much more. If youâ€™re actively using Facebook or Twitter to drive people to your site or blog, Google analytics will show you how your social marketing activity is working for you as well.</p>\r\n<p>This week, if youâ€™re not setup on Google Analytics, place a call to your web designer or hosting firm and ask them to set it up.Â  Also, take a close look at your last marketing activity and calculate a few of these metrics.Â  Journal your findings and begin to establish some benchmarks for yourself.</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-07-21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(19, 'Set an Agenda for Sales Success', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p align="center">The most essential factor is persistence - the determination never to allow your energy or enthusiasm to be dampened by the discouragement that must inevitably come.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Â James Whitcomb RileyÂ ~</p>\r\n<p>Now that you have generated interest and set a meeting, what should your agenda be? What information do you want to present to help your prospect understand the benefits of doing business with you? Youâ€™ve already asked qualifying questions in your call to establish whether there would be value in starting a business relationship, so whatâ€™s the next step?</p>\r\n<p>The key is to set an agenda for yourself to use during your sales meetings. Formulating a sales plan will allow you to stay on task and hit all the major points you want to cover during limited face time. It is critical to build rapport with your prospect during this initial meeting. After youâ€™ve greeted them, itâ€™s important to qualify them on a personal level by getting to know their situation and life experiences. Knowing something about their career, marital status, parenting, community, and home ownership status may help you understand whether they fit the profile of your ideal customer. Meeting with the prospect in their surroundings will give you the ability to pick up little nuances of their personality and give you the opportunity to ask questions as you build rapport during your opening conversation.</p>\r\n<p>You then want to transition the focus to business and discuss their daily challenges to discover if this translates to a need for your product or service. It is your duty to understand their vision from those areas of concern and determine whether what you offer is an appropriate pathway to their desired solution. Be ready with an expanded version of the presentation you made over the phone about the key benefits of your main product or service, but you do not need to rely on a formal presentation at this point.</p>\r\n<p>The purpose of this initial meeting is to gather information. If it is determined that both parties want to go forward, set-up a future meeting where you can give your formal presentation.</p>\r\n<p>Even if they are not your ideal customer, already utilize a similar product or service, or a business opportunity simply doesnâ€™t exist, there may still be opportunity. If you have been effective in letting your personality and expertise come through, you can conclude by asking for an appropriate referral and see what you can do to steer them in the right direction in your network.</p>\r\n<p>This week, setÂ your sales agenda for your first face-to-face meeting with a prospect.</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted<em>.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-02-02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(20, 'Thank You Goes a Long Way', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p align="center">You don''t close a sale, you open a relationship if you want tobuildÂ a long-term, successful enterprise.Â Â </p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Patricia Fripp ~</p>\r\n<p>Whether an initial meeting is successful or not, follow-up is crucial to your long-term success. In an age where we just shoot off a quick email after a meeting, the art of truly saying thank you has been lost. The 5 minutes you take to write a thoughtful, sincere, and personalized thank you letter can do wonders for paving the path of your long-term success. At a time when decision makers are flooded with calls and appointments, saying thank you could make the difference in separating yourself from the competition. Thank you letters after sales calls are never a waste time, whether you won, lost, or arenâ€™t sure if youâ€™ve gained the business. A good formula for the follow-up letter is as follows:Â <strong>Thank the person for their time.</strong>Â Everybody is busy and there is only so much time in a day. Show that you appreciate them taking the time to attentively listen to you.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong>Mention something personal that you appreciated.</strong>Â The fact that you remembered a personal detail or story shows that you are an active listener and can help build rapport.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong>Review the process that you went through with them.</strong>Â It is important to give a brief summary of what you discussed. Address how your service or product can be a solution to their problem, which you discovered by conducting an assessment before your meeting.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong>Identify future activity.</strong>Â  Make sure you leave the door open for a future relationship as you say goodbye and sign off in the summary letter. It is important to set realistic expectations for follow-up going forward, whether itâ€™s to continue the sales cycle or just add the contact to your database.</p>\r\n<p align="left">After the letter, make sure you update your Customer Relationship Management (CRM) system and identify how you plan on keeping them a part of your sales cycle. Put solid prospects into your normal CRM system. Add contacts that you are not yet doing business with into a &quot;tickle file,&quot; sending them occasional updates to keep you and your services top-of-mind so they can actively refer you business. It is critical to not burn any bridges. Whether you close the deal or not, there is always a possibility that the prospect may have a need you can meet at a later date or may know somebody else that you can service effectively.</p>\r\n<p align="left">This week, create a draft of the thank you letter you will use to follow-up with a prospect, knowing that youâ€™ll need to customize it each time.</p>\r\n<p align="left">The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted<em>.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-02-08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(21, 'It''s Not So Cold Afterall', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p align="center">Permanence, perseverance and persistence in spite of all obstacles, discouragements, and impossibilities: It is this, that in all things distinguishes the strong soul from the weak.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Thomas Carlyle ~</p>\r\n<p>The cold call strikes fear into the hearts of many. The wordÂ <em>cold</em>Â is very appropriate, since some of us get chills up and down our spine at the thought of picking up the phone to call somebody you have never met.</p>\r\n<p>One of the first things you can do is gear yourself to theÂ <em>host</em>Â mentality, instead of being somebody who just wants something.Â <em>Hosting</em>Â is a term we use in our networking training to describe the mindset in which you think of everyone you meet as a person you are welcoming into your life.</p>\r\n<p>You must create of sense of welcoming in your cold call. It is always a good idea to research your prospects before you make the initial contact. The fact that you took the time to educate yourself will always give you a leg up when trying to connect with your target. This allows you to plant a seed in the prospectâ€™s mind: if you took the time to get to know their company before calling them the first time, they begin to picture the quality of service you would provide them as a client.</p>\r\n<p>During the course of the call, it is critical to maintain a warm, graceful attitude as you introduce yourself and continue to learn about the prospect and their company. Monitor your attitude and have the expectation that no matter what, youâ€™re meeting a new friend. No matter how many times you have been rejected in the past, youâ€™re going to keep going and make new friends.</p>\r\n<p>The most important part of the cold call is not reading from a script. It is clear to the person on the other end when you are not having a natural conversation. Make an effort to give them a sense of who you are and help them understand what makes you and your product or service unique and able to fit their need. Set expectations for follow-up and continue the sales cycle.</p>\r\n<p>This week, research the companies you are cold calling before picking-up the phone.</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-06-16', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(22, 'Wake Up and Smell the Competition!', 'Rich Lyons, CEO, Lyons Consulting Group, Finance and Growth Coach', '<p align="center">I have been up against tough competition all my life.I wouldn''t know how to get along without it.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Walt Disney ~</p>\r\n<p>Whether they tell you or not, a customer who is shopping you, checking out your goods or services, is also looking at your competition. Even if they feel 95% certain that you are &quot;the one,&quot; they are still seeing what else is out there. What does that mean to you? You canâ€™t afford to be ignorant when it comes to knowing what your competitors are up to - especially what they are charging for what they are doing.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Talk price up front.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Part of being wise to your competitorâ€™s pricing means having a direct conversation with your customer about what they are looking for. Donâ€™t wait to the end make sure you are in the right ball park. Find out up front what they are looking to spend and why theyâ€™ve chosen that amount. Do they have financial limitations? Are they hard bargainers and just looking for a deal no matter what? Understanding their budget and motivations will help you keep a leg up on your customers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ask Around.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Talk to other people in the industry. Even if your customers give you an idea of what the competition has offered, donâ€™t consider it 100% reliable. As human beings we tend to consciously and unconsciously inflate or deflate prices. It is very common for us to hear bachelor level new college graduates say that the market is paying $40 to $70 thousand dollars which is true in certain industries, but definitely isnâ€™t a true average. The real number is closer to $30 thousand depending on the time of year and the economy. If you ask around to others you know in the industry, you can get accurate statistics or at least averages. Get yourself grounded in reality for your pricing.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Know your breakeven.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Above all else, know what your breakeven is. Regardless of your customerâ€™s budget and your competition, you still need to be able to make pricing choices that bring you profit. And if you find thatâ€™s getting you priced out every time, it might be time to rethink your business model.</p>\r\n<p>This week, select one prospect to focus on and look at your pricing for them. Calculate your breakeven for what you are quoting, ask around to see how that stands up in the industry, and then be bold in talking to your prospect about their pricing expectations and desire. Youâ€™ll be surprised to discover that a little bit of homework can go a long way to winning the project.</p>\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted<em>.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-06-23', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(23, 'Creating a Brochure? Write Yourself an Insurance Policy', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">As a general rule, the most successful man is the man who has the best information.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Benjamin Disraeli ~</p>\r\n<p>Is your marketing plan finished and youâ€™re ready to engage a designer or copywriter to create your new website or brochure? Protect yourself from runaway creative.Â  Take twenty minutes and write a creative brief.Â  Itâ€™s not a guarantee, but itâ€™s a step in the right direction in making sure your piece is on-strategy and on-budget.</p>\r\n<p>A creative brief can save you money and headaches; most importantly, it can get everyone working on the project on the same page.Â  The key components of a creative brief include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Deliverables needed â€“ e.g., flat mail, multi-page brochure, landing page</li>\r\n  <li>Overview of the project â€“ give your creative team some background</li>\r\n  <li>Communication objective -- what do you want this piece to motivate the reader to do, think or feel?</li>\r\n  <li>Call to action -- how will you lead them to the next step . . . a landing page, a toll-free number, a QR code?</li>\r\n  <li>Primary audience â€“ what are the demographics, firmagraphics, or psychographics of your audience?</li>\r\n  <li>Your identity statement â€“ what is the one, main benefit that you deliver and that separates you from your competition?</li>\r\n  <li>Value Proposition â€“ is there a quantifiable value that you want to be expressed in the piece, e.g., &quot;we can increase your sales by 20%&quot;?</li>\r\n  <li>Key messages â€“ what are the benefit-oriented points that you want to get across that support your business identity?</li>\r\n  <li>Tone and Image â€“ how should the piece be communicated, from a visual and/or written perspective?</li>\r\n  <li>Budget and Timeline â€“ what price range are you able to pay for this piece and when do you have to have it completed by?</li>\r\n  <li>Other â€“ any other information that you feel your creative team should know</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Words to the Wise</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>It may be tempting, but donâ€™t pay for creativity and make all the decisions yourself.Â  Let your creative team and staff in on the decision making.Â  When it comes to creative, two heads are always better than one.Â  If youâ€™re a one-man show, youâ€™re guaranteed to miss something.</li>\r\n  <li>Donâ€™t over-manage your creative resources.Â  They are professionals in their field for a reason; let them do their job.Â  You should provide logos and general look and feel for consistency.Â  However, donâ€™t dictate specific words, phrases, type style, or layout.</li>\r\n  <li>State performance requirements with a budget and timeline. Donâ€™t be afraid to have this discussion; itâ€™s better to be clear up front and state your budget cap so there are no surprises in the end.Â  Make sure your creative team knows their deadline and then do everything possible to support them in a timely manner when they ask you for information.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>So before you send your hired creative person on a wild goose chase to create your piece, give them some direction.Â  Use a creative brief to enable communication among all parties and ensure that your goals and objectives are met.</p>\r\n<p>This week, begin compiling some of the elements of a creative brief such as identity statement and key messages.</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '0000-00-00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(24, 'Budget Now . . . or Pay Later', 'Rich Lyons, CEO, Lyons Consulting Group, Finance and Growth Coach', '<p align="center">Reduce your plan to writing. The moment you complete this, you will have definitely given concrete form to the intangible desire.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Napoleon Hill ~</p>\r\n<p>Budgeting is an essential planning tool for the small business owner. Like mapping your route before attempting a hike in unfamiliar territory, budgeting is a process you avoid at your own peril.Â  Moreover, as a business owner or potential business owner, developing your budget can be one of the first places your dreams start taking shape.</p>\r\n<p>Ask ten business owners about their budgeting process, and youâ€™ll probably get nine and a half responses that will leave you guessing or hopeless.</p>\r\n<p>A budget is a plan that anticipates revenue and expenses. Once developed, it corresponds to your P &amp; L categories (if you donâ€™t have a P &amp; L, get that going first) and helps you track actual performance against your expectations. During the year, as you see actual versus anticipated figures in each category, you adjust accordingly. Your budget acts to keep you oriented to your profitable performance.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Top down or bottom up?</strong></p>\r\n<p>You may have begun your business asking what kind of resources do I have to get my product out the door, or market my services.</p>\r\n<p>In budgeting, start instead by asking, &quot;What would this business need to bring in for it to be worth the investment of my life energy?&quot;Â  Put your bottom line profit at the top of the page and youâ€™ll begin asking more productive questions, like &quot;How much more could I sell if Iâ€¦?&quot; and &quot;Am I really getting the bang for the buck Iâ€™m spending onâ€¦?&quot;</p>\r\n<p><strong>What to include</strong></p>\r\n<p>A basic budget includes three main components.</p>\r\n<p><em>Sales and other revenue</em>Â While you have permission to dream here, your success will ultimately depend on your ability to make realistic predictions and follow through on your plans to meet them. If this is not your first year in operation, estimate your sales/revenue somewhere between 80 and 120% of last yearâ€™s for the most realistic assessment, depending on your desire to economize or aggressively grow. Whatever figure you arrive at, it should be based on a thorough analysis of your sales activity and what it should return.</p>\r\n<p><em>Costs &amp; expenses</em>Â Fixed costs are ones you will payÂ <em>no matter what</em>Â to run your business, such as office rent or salaries. They are not necessarilyÂ <em>permanentlyÂ </em>fixed (by that definition there would be no true fixed costs in business)â€”just fixed for the period of time you are analyzing. Variable costs (generally synonymous with cost of goods sold) are those thatÂ <em>fluctuate</em>Â with the sales, such as service, materials, packaging, and delivery charges.</p>\r\n<p><em>Profit</em>Â is your expected revenue minus variable and fixed costs.</p>\r\n<p>You will most likely go through several iterations in each of these categories. You could, for example, include a high, medium, and low estimate of sales. In addition to affecting your revenue in, each estimate would produce different expectations for variable costs. Expect that you will need to adjust and readjust to hit your profit targets.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Budget cumulatively</strong></p>\r\n<p>Not every budget has to balance. It is possible that a new venture will run &quot;in the red&quot; for a startup period and break even over time. Thatâ€™s why your budget should also include a total cumulative profit line. Your expenses may outpace revenue for four months, for example, and your cumulative budget will show you that it will take another three months to recoup those losses and have a profitable business. Remember â€“ profit is not what you pay yourself, so include a salary.</p>\r\n<p>Get in the habit of budgeting year in and year out, and youâ€™ll get better each year at predicting revenue and controlling costs. You will then be better able to tell how long it will take for you to see the bottom-line effects of big decisions like adding staff or purchasing equipment. Budgeting is the predictive phase of understanding your profit and loss. Once youâ€™re in operation, your P &amp; L statement is analogous to your budget in rear view, showing your actual revenue and expenses over a particular period of time.</p>\r\n<p>Review your budget monthly and make adjustments as necessary to predict your needs and opportunities with increasing accuracy. When you accept that your sales and production will almost never match your budget exactly, you can delight in the experiment of bringing your financial reality more in line with your vision.</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-05-05', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(25, 'Customer Loyalty: Thinking Beyond the Frequent Buyer Punch Card', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p><em>By Michelle Lanter Smith</em><em>Marketing Coach</em><em>CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing &amp; Sales Solutions</em></p>\r\n<p align="center"><em>You don''t earn loyalty in a day. You earn loyalty day-by-day.</em>~ Jeffrey Gitomer ~</p>\r\n<p>Thereâ€™s more to customer loyalty than running a customer points program or frequent buyer card. Yes, these can be important tools for small businesses to implement in order to incent repurchase and repeat visits.Â  However, there are otherâ€”just as importantâ€”factors that contribute to customer loyalty.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Be loyal to your customer first.</strong>Â  How often do we spend our time and resources on trying to attract new clients when in fact, we should spending more money and energy cultivating our current ones?Â  Not only are the odds so much better in closing deals with existing clients versus new clients, but existing clients are a great source of referrals.Â  People tend to hang around people who are similar to them, like a bee hive.Â  Their communication patterns are established and ideas and recommendations flow freely with a strong sense of credibility.Â </li>\r\n  <li><strong>Bolster customer communication.</strong>Â  Part of customer loyalty and retention is maintaining regular contact with your most profitable customers.Â  Communication to your best customers should take the form of showing your appreciation and providing new learning experiences to add value to your customerâ€™s life.Â  Send special thank-you notes, surprise gifts and regular communication such as newsletter to connect with them.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Leverage the small business secret.</strong>Â  Small businesses always have the advantage in connecting with customers and building long-term, meaningful relationships.Â  Unlike large companies, your passion for helping your customers will shine through your one-on-one attention and personalization; this is very difficult for large companies to duplicate.Â  As a small business, you have the ability to earn trust as you serve them like no other.Â  As customer evangelist guru Ben McConnell states, &quot;Small businesses thrive on outstanding customer loyalty.Â  Itâ€™s their currency of growth and their best differentiator.&quot;</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Reward for customer retention.</strong>Â  Here lies the key metric to customer loyaltyâ€”how many stick with you through the years.Â  However, measuring customer retention is only half the battle.Â  Your staff needs to be rewarded for customer retention.Â  Unlike large companies that tend to reward on new business only, consider rewarding your staff when a large client sticks around year after year.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>So if you if want to put customer loyalty to work in your business, you should review the various frequent buyer plans out there (point systems, punch cards, membership clubs) and select one that will motivate the buying behavior you want to stimulate.Â  However, remember, itâ€™s more than punch cards that earns customer loyalty.Â  Itâ€™s more about earning trust and relationship building.</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-05-12', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(26, 'Launching and Using Your Advisory Board', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p align="center">Listen to advice and accept correction and then in the end, you will be wise.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Book of Proverbs ~</p>\r\n<p>Think of an advisory board as a group of mentors.</p>\r\n<p>Most small businesses are not in a position to pay for a board of directors or an advisory board, but that doesnâ€™t mean you canâ€™t get advice. While the very term implies a group of people meeting at the same time, that may or may not be how you manage to use your advisory board. If we think of the purpose of the advisory board as a way to meet your need for mentoring, support, and coaching, then one of the ways to get an advisory board is to hire coaches. Different coaches have different skill sets. Some have a very broad skill set and some have a very narrow skill set. I personally hire an outside business and finance coach, sales coach, and spiritual mentor, given that our organization operates with a higher purpose and mission that I consider to be a major part of my service to our world.</p>\r\n<p>In composing a more traditional advisory board, who should you ask? Â First of all, you must have someone who understands business development. Marketing and sales could be included in this personâ€™s expertise, or you may choose to engage another person specifically for that function. Next you need a member who understands finance, budget, planning, and reading a profit and loss statement. Someone in operations can advise you on hiring staff, managing staff, productivity with staff, and dealing with staff issues and problems. In addition to that, consider a legal person. Depending on your products or services, your advisory board may include a systems expert and a subject matter expert.</p>\r\n<p>Some people want to know if they should ask their friends. As a general rule, you get what you pay for. Friends are frequently uncomfortable and also donâ€™t feel responsibility at the same level as someone youâ€™ve hired.</p>\r\n<p>Next is the issue of empowering your advisory board. If you speak with advisors apart from the official meeting of the board, ask yourself what are the takeaways and conclusions that you come to in a meeting with them, and how do you empower them in the next meeting? Each time you convene your board, review the previous meeting. Talk about changes made and not made since last time, so that advisors can then dig into what the barriers are to getting done what they suggested getting done. They will help you discover whether the barriers relate to lack of resources and skills, or whether it is a psychological block. A good mentor or advisor will help you overcome all types, with some being better at the psychological side and some at skills and solutions. Â </p>\r\n<p>For most of you, until you are operating in excess of a million dollars a year â€“ and probably above 2 million â€“ an official advisory board may be premature depending on the business and what you are facing. In addition to having multiple advisory boards for our organization, we have a finance committee. All meet quarterly, and our immediate operating board meets monthly. Some entrepreneurs pay for peer management programs that create advisory boards or councils for them. These can cost easily anywhere from 500 to 1000 per month. Some of these include an hour of coaching.</p>\r\n<p>Prior to a million dollars a year, your primary objective is developing your business and your money and time is better spent on a business coach who understands sales, and a sales development program that focuses you on growing. Just make sure at that level that you have a solid accountant who truly understands business, and that you account for your time as a sales professional, a delivery professional, manager, and as an owner. You can hire other experts in their area without having to have your own board. When you get to the point that these functions need to talk to each other and that you want them to help you strategize and hold you accountable, then thatâ€™s a point at which you may also need to begin paying for them that service.</p>\r\n<p>In large corporations, board members are paid $30,000 to $150,000 annually per year for quarterly meetings and participation in committees such as compensation and development, finance, and legal. With these board positions in public corporations, there is also an issue of legal liability and the need to carry errors and omissions insurance. We mention this only so that you can understand where you are headedâ€”advisory boards have no legal fiduciary responsibility, nor do they vote on corporate matters. They are simply advisory, which reduces your accountability to them and their accountability.</p>\r\n<p>Owning your small business doesnâ€™t mean you have to go it alone. Enjoy the camaraderie and idea sharing as you develop a fully functioning advisory board.</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2011-05-19', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(27, 'Positive Attitude, Powerful Sales Calls ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p align="center">Quit looking for the people you&rsquo;re looking for andstart looking for the people that are looking for you.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Doug Firebaugh ~</p>\r\n<p>When you pick up the phone to make a sales call, you have two jobs: to create interest and excitement in your product or service and to establish whether the customer or potential customer has a need you can meet.</p>\r\n<p>Before you pick up the phone, ask yourself whetherÂ <em>you</em>Â are excited about what you are about to sell. Are you in a position where your enthusiasm will be contagious, or are you feeling sorry for yourself about how the last call went, or thinking of problems unrelated to the call ahead? If you don&rsquo;t feel like you&rsquo;re about to unleash a positive virus into the world, stop a moment. Call someone who understands your vision for your business and give yourself a pep talk as they listen. Expressing your fear or your upset beforehand (even to someone else&rsquo;s voice mail) is all it often takes to clear your mind and focus your intention before the call. An &quot;I hear you!&quot; or &quot;Go get &lsquo;em&quot; from a trusted friend in reply is simply icing on the cake.</p>\r\n<p>Next, make sure you present the product or benefit up front in such a way that you effectively engage your prospect over the phone. Make a true statement about your business&rsquo;s benefit. For example you may say, &quot;Our service saves our clients an average of $5,000 a month.&quot; Hoping you have piqued their interest, you can follow up with, &quot;Do you have a few minutes now to talk with me about your business and see whether we could create similar results for you?&quot; Ideally, you will have some knowledge of their business.</p>\r\n<p>This is where you begin qualifying whether the prospect has a need you can meet. Gear your questions toward gathering data from them. Paradoxically, the more theyÂ <em>give</em>Â you, the more they will actually feelÂ <em>invested</em>Â in you and the likelihood of scoring an in-person meeting improves. That said, beware of talking too long. As soon as you hear that there is interest, set the next action.</p>\r\n<p>In almost every case, you want that action to be a face-to-face meeting.Â  Most of the clients we coach find that even if they are good closers on the phone, they can double their close rate in-person. Leave them wanting more and you are likely to get more too.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" align="left">Stay tuned for next week&rsquo;s tip on setting the agenda for a meeting and join the June 16th Â webinar for even more on powerful sales calls.The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted<em>.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-05-25', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(28, 'Cash Flow Problem . . . or is it? ', 'Rich Lyons, CEO, Lyons Consulting Group, Finance and Growth Coach', '<p align="center">Happiness is a positive cash flow.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Fred Adler ~</p>\r\n<p>Cash flow is a matter of anticipation and realistic planning. When most small business owners begin operating, they mistakenly anticipate that whatever they bill or invoice for goods and services will be immediately available to them as cash. Managing cash flow is about refining the accuracy with which you anticipate money coming back to you.</p>\r\n<p>Some people use the phrase &quot;cash flow problem&quot; to describe situations that are really profitability problems. If you have expenses you currently cannot cover, but know that adequate cash is due to you in receivables, you have a true cash flow problem. In this situation, banks are typically willing to consider lines of credit for as much as 75% to 80% of your receivables that have aged less than 90 days. And often you may be able to negotiate better terms with your customers, and take a percentage of your fees upfront to help cover your expenses.</p>\r\n<p>If you simply havenâ€™t billed enough to cover expenses, this is a profitability problem. A bank line of credit will likely not be an option for you, and your choices must revolve around increasing sales or cutting expenses.</p>\r\n<p>This week, determine if your company is experiencing a cash flow issue or a profitability issue . . . or neither.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-04-14', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(29, 'Business on the Cloud', 'Demitrus T. Evans, J.D., LLMTEIL Firms, LLCStep-It-Up 2010 Winner', '<p align="left">Please note: The information contained in this article is not the opinion or advice of American Family Insurance andÂ is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.Â  Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Communication is at the heart of e-commerce . . . ~</p>\r\n<p align="center">Meg Whitman</p>\r\n<p align="left">There are over 350 million websites in existence, with more being created daily. Of course with the internet available at our workplaces, in our homes, on our televisions, and on our phones, we can assume that more business is being done online than ever before, and that the usage will only continue to increase. With these facts, we business owners must be careful to follow legal guidelines in cyber business, and know and understand the legal risks involved.</p>\r\n<p align="left">When businesses sell goods and services on the internet, as with a brick and mortar business transaction, contracts are involved and rules must be followed. Being on the internet does not make it any less likely that situations could go awry so make sure you understand the implications.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong><em>CONTRACTS</em></strong>Contracts can be complicated or very simple, depending on the subject matter. It just means that there are agreements between two or more which establish mutual expectations and rights. Contracts are normally written, as we think of them, but they can also be oral. When forming a contract there are two rules (among many others) that must be followed. You must never contract with minors, or the legally insane. Essentially all parties to the contract must know that they are contracting and must be legally, and emotionally stable to consent to the agreement. Oral contracts can be proven, but there are some contracts that must be in writing, e.g., contracts for land, products over a $500 and obligations which will require a year to accomplish must be in writing. If you want to be certain your contract will be enforceable, itâ€™s best to get it in writing.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong><em>DISCLAIMERS</em></strong>On the internet you want to make sure your business is not contracting unknowingly. So make sure you have disclaimers on your websites as well as your e-mails. Make sure you have them in a typeface large enough to be visible. Minors may be drawn to your site, simply because of certain words or pictures that you are using. However, there are all sorts of laws to protect minors so be sure that if you are inviting them, that it is your intention to do so, and that there is nothing deceptive which may cause legal issues.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong><em>MULTIJURISDICTIONAL</em></strong>When doing business online you are practicing business internationally; be mindful that the laws where your products and or services end up may be different than where you are physically located. The federal government, through the US Constitution, regulates commerce between states and countries. IfÂ  a high number of your followers are in a state different from yours, you may be viewed as doing business in that state, which means if there is a problem you would have to go there for litigation. This could be costly for you.</p>\r\n<p align="left">Speaking of costs, a lack of knowledge and awareness of where your clients are, and thus, where you are &quot;doing business,&quot; could have tax implications for the business as well.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong><em>SHIPPING AND INSURANCE</em></strong>Depending how you are sending goods from your internet site, you may be responsible for costs and insurance. You must understand shipping costs like &quot;FOB.&quot; Make sure you know if you will you be responsible for the goods once in the hands of the carrier, or until the end user receives the goods. Know if the purchaser knows your intentions, and have your rules and standard shipping procedure conveniently located on the site. If you donâ€™t have these things in order now, you should probably include them. You should also consider purchasing additional insurance which covers any mistakes, or reliance on the website.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong><em>INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY</em></strong>Avoid legal problems with trademark and copyright infringement by carefully researching your business name, phrases and symbols. Determine if the mark or material is registered with United States Trademark and Patent office and/or the US Copyright Office by another party. If they are not registered to someone else then you register them and indicate the status of the registration on your website, e-mail or blog. Although Intellectual property searches can be time consuming, it is very easy to begin this journey by reviewing the name, mark, material through the search engines. You are looking for something similar or confusing. If you use any intellectual property which belongs to others in your business advertisement, make sure you cite it as belonging to them.</p>\r\n<p align="left"><strong><em>SPAM</em></strong>Lastly, as wonderful as your business advertising is, not all people are happy to receive it, so youÂ <strong><em>must</em></strong>Â have a way for the receiver to &quot;opt out&quot; or &quot;unsubscribe&quot; from your e-mail blasts.Â  In your e-mails you may not use misleading information in the body or subject or to /from of e-mails to entice someone to open them and you have to say that the purpose of the e-mail is for advertisement.Â  Incidentally, a cyber home for the business is a non-reality and you must have a physical address that the e-mails can be traced to.</p>\r\n<p align="left">Doing e-business, operating in cyberspace and business on the cloud may be the wave of the future, but as business owners we must think of the internet simply as a tool which we use with wisdom and skill.</p>\r\n<p align="left">To consult with Demitrus Evans, contact her at 708-531-1740 or at devans@teilfirms.com</p>', '', '', '2011-04-28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
