(30, 'Facing Rejection', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p align="center">A rejection is nothing more than a necessary step in the pursuit of success.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Bo Bennett ~</p>\r\n<p>Most people face rejection without ever really facing it. They''ve already imagined the rejection before it happens.</p>\r\n<p>There are two kinds of resistance that lead to rejection.</p>\r\n<p><em>External resistance</em>Â is the type people most often think about and fearfully plan for that is, the resistance your customer or prospect may have to buying your product or service. But our biggest challenge in supporting small business owners in growing their business is actually to face their<em>internal resistance</em>.</p>\r\n<p><em>Internal resistance</em>Â is the resistanceÂ <em>youÂ </em>bring. It''s what keeps you from getting out and meeting people, introducing yourself and your business, finding out their needs, offering a solution and asking for their business. In short, it''s your resistance to fully and powerfully presenting yourself and your product</p>\r\n<p>Too often in selling, small businesspeople go in like the salesperson in comedy routines saying, &quot;You don''t want to buy an encyclopedia, do you? That person has already decided on rejection and is hoping someone will reject rejection.</p>\r\n<p>Taking risks is the key to learning how to face rejection.</p>\r\n<p>Risk is reaching out. Risk is asking people to talk about something. Risk is asking people about themselves. Risk is asking them if a solution you are offering sounds interesting to them. Risk is asking what it will take to do the deal. Risk is asking when you can start.</p>\r\n<p>Once you''re in the habit of asking and risking, the next important step in overcoming rejection is to assume that rejection is the next step in the sale. Resistance is high quality information about where the person is coming from. Being interested in the substance of their rejection will reap great benefits.</p>\r\n<p>All of this assumes, of course, that for your own integrity you would never sell your product if it weren''t correct and proper for the individual.</p>\r\n<p>With practice, top salespeople learn to adjust their thinking about rejection. To them, maybe means yes and no means maybe. The question isÂ <em>what does this person needs to hear and receive in order for me to make this sale</em>?</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-03-03', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(31, 'Zap! Mind Harvesting is the First Step to Generating Creative Ideas', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">The value of an idea lies in the using of it.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Thomas Edison ~</p>\r\n<p>How many times have you had a great idea but moments later it''s gone? As entrepreneurs, we tend to be inspired quite often. Sometimes it''s during our daily commute when a new billboard grabs our attention, or other times it''s while we''re doing something totally unproductive, like watching &quot;Everybody Loves Raymond&quot; and &quot;Seinfeld&quot; reruns. These momentary interruptions of break-through thinking are foundational nuggets of our creative juices. If harvested and nurtured properly, some of these ideas can become true, marketing genius. They can result in creative renditions of first-class marketing notions, ready to give your business the bang it needs.</p>\r\n<p>As you know, ideas may last only a second or two and then they disappear into thin air. Here''s a tip on how to harvest the most out of those flashes of brilliance that your wonderfully creative brain is producing at random moments. The tip is very simple. Keep a small, 4 x 6 pocket notebook with you at all times.</p>\r\n<p>When you have a thought that seems to be central to your business or a problem that you''re stewing on, grab your pocket notebook and jot down your idea immediately and completely. Let your mind pounce on it and begin to write. Don''t put off your note-taking for even a second. As you write down your thought, related ideas will occur to you . . . write them down too. Don''t ignore them.</p>\r\n<p>Don''t judge your thoughts and try to decide what is good and what is bad. Just keep writing down your thoughts until your head is empty. Just like a frog''s tongue is lightning fast flicking out to capture the nearby fly. Zap! You got it - a marketing embryo that could grow and blossom into a phenomenal marketing initiative.</p>\r\n<p>Once you''ve captured the essence of your idea, put your notebook away and go on with what you were doing. When another idea comes along, pull out your notebook and write it down too. Take good care of your notebook, even after it''s filled and you''ve flushed out the better ideas at your desk using your normal means. You may find that there will be use for these ideas preserved in your notebooks for entirely different projects for years to come.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-03-17', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(32, 'Who''s Got the Time? How to Get your Newsletter out without Taxing your Resources', 'Teri Latter Director of Program Management Brillante Multicultural Marketing Group', '<p align="center">A big part of finding the right resources is knowing what to look for. . . ~ Matthew Lesko ~</p>\r\n<p>You know you should do a newsletter- it''s the perfect way to stay in front of customers, be they past, present or future clients. But you''re busy running your business and you don''t have the time to make the commitment that a regular newsletter requires. For now the newsletter is falling into the &quot;shoulda, coulda, woulda&quot; category.</p>\r\n<p>What does it take to make it more feasible? A little planning and some easy-to-come-by resources.</p>\r\n<p>By now, as an owner of a business, you are a fount of information on your industry or on the service you provide. Can you spend perhaps 30 minutes a week to write a paragraph about what you know? If you can make that commitment, then you should consider writing a blog to share that information. You can add a blog to your website or you can create a standalone blog.</p>\r\n<p>What does this have to do with a newsletter? Well, if you write your blogs so that all the ones you create in a given month are somewhat related to each other, then you can bring two, three, or all four of them together into a newsletter article. You might even have enough for two newsletter articles.</p>\r\n<p>This still leaves the question of putting the newsletter together and now that a blog has been recommended, you''re going to need to do that, too, so we''re back to the issue of simply not having the time to do all this. Here''s where free resources come in.</p>\r\n<p>College students are always looking for internships that given them the opportunity to do real-world work and in many instances, they do these internships just for the experience, not for pay. An intern can research the different blog platforms available and determine if it makes sense for you to do your blog on your website or standalone. Your intern can take care of loading up your blog and can even review and edit it so that it is search-engine optimized. You can also have the intern review the blog periodically to see if any comments and have been posted.</p>\r\n<p>An intern can also take care of creating an email template for you through an e-marketing service provider and upload your email database onto the platform. They can review your blog posts and do the writing necessary to create a newsletter article. They can then take care of loading the story into the template and sending it out. You'';ll probably want to do the intro letter to the newsletter and take a look at the finished product before it goes out, but other than that, you can hand most of the work over to an eager intern.</p>\r\n<p>Will one intern be able to do all this? That will depend on the skills of the individual, but most likely one person can do both the blog and the setting up of the newsletter and sending it out. You may require a second person to actually write the newsletter articles.</p>\r\n<p>The result is that with an investment of 30 minutes a week of writing, the time to find an intern or two, and time once a month to write an opening letter for your newsletter, you now have both a blog and a newsletter. Use your keywords so that both are search engine optimized and you''ve also increased the likelihood of your business being found on the web.</p>\r\n<p>This week, carve out the time to write one blog post and then block out time on your calendar in the upcoming weeks to continue writing. At the same time, start looking for college interns to support your efforts.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-03-31', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(33, 'Observant Listening: The First Step to Embracing Soulful Leadership ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">At the deepest level, the leader is the symbolic soul of the group. ~ Deepak Chopra ~</p>\r\n<p>As a small business owner, leadership is a term that you might find expressed often by academics and consultants but not as a part of your everyday activities or even consciousness. After all, we are burdened with the day-to-day operations of the business, customer satisfaction issues, and new business opportunities. Leadership, per se, is a luxury available to the executive suite at Fortune 1000 companies. However, is it really? Leadership, according to Deepak Chopra, author and spiritual guide, is shared not only in the workforce, but in the home, church, and personal relationships. Each of us must step into the role of leader, taking responsibility first for directing our own lives, and then for interacting with other people.</p>\r\n<p>In Chopra''s most recent book,Â <em>The Soul of Leadership</em>, he writes that one of the first steps to becoming a great leader is by actively listening to the needs of your group. People don'';t wear signs announcing what they need. It must be observed, processed, and noted.</p>\r\n<p>&quot;To be the soul of the group, a leader must correctly perceive what everyone needs and then put her perceptions into action,&quot; states Chopra.</p>\r\n<p>The characteristics of a good listener are not new- your mother probably taught you many of them before the age of seven. And, in fact, developing good listening skills is not only critical to leading, but also to persuading, loving, and serving. Here are the seven things, according to Chopra, that make you a good listener.</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n  <p>1. Not interrupting.</p>\r\n  <p>2. Showing that you empathize not criticizing, arguing, or patronizing.</p>\r\n  <p>3. Establishing a physical sense of closeness without invading personal space.</p>\r\n  <p>4. Observing body language and letting yours show you are not distracted but attentive.</p>\r\n  <p>5. Offering your own self-disclosures, but not too many, or too soon.</p>\r\n  <p>6. Understanding the context of the other person''s life.</p>\r\n  <p>7. Listening from all four levels: body, mind, heart, and soul.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>As with anything, practice makes perfect- so begin sharpening your basic leadership skills right now.</p>\r\n<p>After you''ve read this tip, closed up your computer and walked away from your desk, be mindful of your next interpersonal experience with another human being or group of co-workers, volunteers, friends, or relatives. Look closely at the person or group with both your mind and your soul, and ask yourself- what does this group or person need?</p>\r\n<p>Jot down the &quot;gut&quot; feelings that hit you- maybe one or two words that quickly flash across the brain. Then, momentarily, try to imagine yourself as if you were actually that person or the collective consciousness of the group (i.e., put yourself in their shoes.) Again, immediately write down a word or two that comes to mind.</p>\r\n<p>Finally, ask yourself, what response can I provide that will address their current needs today?</p>\r\n<p>Upon this immediate reflection to each of these questions, incorporate your vision for the future state of things whether it is your business/group or your personal family desire. What you''ll discover is that your natural strengths will come out in your response to the situation and you will grow along with the people you are helping--symbolically merging the hearts, minds, and souls of the group.</p>\r\n<p>And that, Chopra writes, defines leadership as &quot;the symbolic soul of a group.&quot;</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-02-10', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(34, 'First Come, First Served: Why Your Office is Not a Short-Order Deli ', 'Leslie Shreve Founder, Productive Day', '<p align="center"><em>The key is not to prioritize what''s on your schedule but to schedule your priorities.</em></p>\r\n<p align="center"><em>~ Stephen R. Covey ~</em></p>\r\n<p>Over the years, in your endless search for work day bliss, I imagine you''ve established your routines at work for getting things done. You may have followed the advice of the hottest gurus or just created your own way to balance all the demands made upon you from moment to moment.</p>\r\n<p><em>So how''s your routine working?</em></p>\r\n<p>Are you stuck in a few work day ruts? Do you recognize when you''re stuck? Have you been buried by an avalanche of information, succumbed to multi-tasking and gotten sucked into the greatest source of an unproductive work day<em>Â - reactivity?</em></p>\r\n<p>Let me share with you 3 common road-side ruts you may find yourself in these days. Are you ready to steer your way out of them and get back on the road to peak productivity?</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Rut #1: Treating everything on a &quot;first come, first served&quot; basis</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>I have clients who have told me they &quot;live from their Inbox&quot; or they complete things as they show up, making it a priority. Do you do that too? Do you drop what you''re doing now so you can do something else just because it''s quick and you''d rather not put one more thing on your to-do list?</p>\r\n<p>If you''re bouncing through your day from task to task as people, phones, and e-mails make more demands on you, you''re treating everyone and everything on a &quot;first come, first served&quot; basis. Then, because everything is a priority, nothing is a priority and your time can easily disappear. Before you know it, you''ve taken care of all those tasks and requests at the expense of your priorities.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Easy solution:</em></strong>Â You''ll feel good about accomplishing a really big, important task or a few little important ones regularly once you learn how to set boundaries, protect your time and keep your focus. Your work day is not a short-order deli. It''s your work day, with an emphasis on your. You never want to lose too much time focusing on what others deem important, when it''s not one of your prioritiesâ€¦ unless it''s your boss making the demands. Then you''ll have to weigh the priorities.</p>\r\n<p>Don''t always have an open-door policy. Don''t pick up the phone every time it rings. Don''t check your e-mail or succumb to the e-mail alerts you have enabled. At other times you will do all of these, but pleaseâ€¦. allow yourself at least two hours each day that are all yours, quiet and uninterrupted, to getâ€¦ thingsâ€¦ done!</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Rut #2: Your task list is on a cocktail napkin</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>When it comes to getting to-dos out of your head, it''s true: anything to write on will do. But it shouldn''t stop there.</p>\r\n<p>I''ve seen clients use napkins both the lunch and cocktail varieties - and even a barf bag from an airplane for writing down to-dos. My client said, &quot;That''s all I had to write on!&quot; Hey, that''s ok with me. It''s is a good first step, but it is not the end of managing those tasks, nor is it even possible to prioritize those tasks with everything else on your plate.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Easy solution:</strong></em>Â Create a &quot;Mission Control&quot; for yourself, electronically. There should be one place in your computer, hopefully within your e-mail system, that you feed all your tasks, reminders, and to-dos so that no matter where or how you collect these, you bring them back to the mother ship. Then you can reduce the reminders around you and you won''t lose tasks and priorities among the mass of information on your desk.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Rut #3: Following the &quot;Touch it once&quot; advice</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>You''ve heard that ago-old advice &quot;touch it once&quot; for your papers, files, e-mails, etc. so you can be most efficient and save time later by not touching it again?</p>\r\n<p>Hogwash! Forget it! If you''re failing at doing this and you feel bad about it, let it go. I hereby free you from the guilt! It''s the most ridiculous bit of advice I''ve ever heard. Well, almost, but that''s for another article. This one is near the top of the charts though.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Easy solution</strong></em>Every time you''re touching something, make a decision on it. That''s the most important point here. You may touch something 10 times in its lifecycle as a task because you''re not always going to resolve it immediately. Not for tasks that require e-mails, calls, research or getting consensus from others. So every time you touch something, anything, make a decision on it and get everything one step closer to done.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-02-24', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(35, 'Resolutions from Business Accelerator Can Start the New Year Right ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">The New Year has taken possession of the clock of time. All hail the duties and possibilities of the coming twelve months!</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Edward Payson Powell ~</p>\r\n<p>Welcome to the year 2011-another year of opportunity and potential business growth! New Year''s resolutions are just as important in your business life as they are in your personal one. Let''s kick-off our third year of the Business Accelerator Program by committing to five key New Year'';s resolutions. Nothing new here for Business Accelerator die hards - just good, solid principles that will help you grow your business.</p>\r\n<p>1.<strong>Â Make your daily DIALS.Â </strong>Whether you set minimum floor at 1 or 25 calls per day, start off the year right by reaching out to people in your network-old clients, new acquaintances, or current business partners. It''s been proven over and over . . .</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>OUTBOUND ACTIVITY yields CONVERSATIONS</li>\r\n  <li>CONVERSATIONS yield MEETINGS</li>\r\n  <li>MEETINGS yield PROPOSALS</li>\r\n  <li>PROPOSALS RESULT IN NEW BUSINESS</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>2.Â <strong>Do your Social Jack</strong>. Schedule 10 minutes on your calendar every day to work in LinkedIn, Facebook, or Twitter. Join a group and participate in a discussion, add a contact or two that you met at yesterday''s meeting, start up a conversation with a connection (this counts toward your dials goal), update your profile, ask for a recommendation.</p>\r\n<p>3.Â <strong>Commit to set a budget for your business this year. I</strong>nclude revenue goals and expense objectives. Commit to review your company financials every month. Learn how to understand and manage the nuances of your profit and loss, balance sheet, and cash flow statements.</p>\r\n<p>4.Â <strong>Refine your elevator pitch and practice it in the mirror.</strong>Â After all, with your increase in selling activity this year, you''ll need an effective opening pitch. Remember the four key elements of the F.A.R.M. system we taught:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Find</strong>Â Their Pain Point</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Answer</strong>Â Their Problem</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Reasons</strong>Â Why You''re Different</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Make</strong>Â Them Want More</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><em>Keep or elevator pitch to under 30 seconds.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>5.Â <strong>Don''t try to be everything to everyone in 2011.</strong>Â Know your sweet spot and what makes you unique compared to your competitors. Clearly and succinctly communicate your uniqueness in all your 2011 marketing collateral. If you''re unclear of your identity, ask your customers! They''ll be most helpful in understanding your strengths and weaknesses and why they like to buy from you.</p>\r\n<p>Want a review on any one of these resolutions? Take a little time to review our recorded symposiums and webinars onÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/">www.AmFamBusinessAccelerator.com</a>. A little refresher might be just the stimulus you need to make it happen in 2011.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-01-13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(36, 'Entrepreneurial DNA Doesn''t Have to be Genetic ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p>You were born to win, but to be a winner, you must plan to win, prepare to win and expect to win. ~ Zig Ziglar ~</p>\r\n<p>Are you the proverbial entrepreneur? Most would say no. However, even though entrepreneurs can come in all shapes and sizes, there are some internal characteristics, I like to call inherent DNA, that are shared by successful business people.</p>\r\n<p>An article recently published by Your Profit Coach, called 130 Reasons Why Some People are Much, Much More Successful in Business than Others, takes a closer look at the successful characteristics of being entrepreneurial. As you read, place a check next to the attributes that you feel you possess. Even if you don''t stack up well against this list, don''t worry. As long as you have the desire and attitude to run your own business, you can learn most of these attributes with practice, self-discipline, and determination.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>See a need in the marketplace or in a customer''s environment and quickly satisfy it.</li>\r\n  <li>Enjoy being their own boss, yet still know how to work within a framework for the sake of profits.</li>\r\n  <li>Have an appetite for hard work.</li>\r\n  <li>Demonstrate extreme self-confidence.</li>\r\n  <li>Resist the temptation to do what is unimportant or the easiest.</li>\r\n  <li>Have the ability to identify what is most essential.</li>\r\n  <li>Have the ability to think quickly and make a wise decision.</li>\r\n  <li>Thrive on changes as their businesses grow.</li>\r\n  <li>Cope with stress by focusing on the end result and not the process of getting there.</li>\r\n  <li>Always have the profit margin in sight and know that their business success is measured by profits.</li>\r\n  <li>Have a high desire to achieve.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>How''d you do? Odds are there were a few that absolutely described you and your behaviors but there were also a few that you could probably improve upon in your day-to-day business dealings. To get on the road to enhancing your entrepreneurial DNA, pick one and put a few rules in place to help make strides in that area.</p>\r\n<p>For instance, if you lack focus on watching the profit margin on every job you do, put these rules in place before you send out that next proposal or reset your prices for the next season. 1) Establish a profit hurdle that every item you sell or every job you propose must exceed. 2) Consider value pricing instead of cost-plus-this usually yields higher margins. 3) Consider alternatives in your product or service offering that would reduce your costs, but not impact customer satisfaction, e.g., bulk orders, lower labor cost, etc.</p>\r\n<p>So go forth--be sure of yourself, your decisions, and your abilities. Oh yes, and one more attribute of successful entrepreneurs that you shouldn''t forget. Even if you''re unsure, know how to wing it and make it look real good.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2011-02-27', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(37, 'The Benefits and Risks of the Company-sponsored Holiday Party ', 'Ann Fisher Founder and President of HR Alternative Consulting Step-It-Up 2010 Winner', '<p align="center">What I don''t like about office Christmas parties is looking for a job the next day.</p>\r\n<p align="center">Phyllis Diller</p>\r\n<p>It is that time again, the company holiday party. Office parties and company-sponsored social functions can be great morale boosters for a company. These functions give employees a chance to become better acquainted in a low pressure setting. Office parties can be a good opportunity to celebrate company success. Unfortunately, there are also some significant risks associated with sponsoring social functions, particularly those where alcohol is served.</p>\r\n<p>Employers that choose to sponsor social events should be aware of the problems that can arise, and take certain precautions. Most of the time, a party will go without a hitch, but any social event brings the possibility, however slim, for personal injuries, third party injuries, and sexual harassment. Also, a company-sponsored party may be subject to claims under both workers'' compensation and general liability insurance.</p>\r\n<p>Recent court rulings in many states have held that persons, including employers who serve liquor may be held liable for injuries to guests or third parties as a result of accidents caused by intoxication. Jury verdicts in some cases ranged into theÂ <strong><em>millions</em></strong>Â of dollars, especially in situations where a drunken employee causes fatal injuries to a third party on the way home from the company event.</p>\r\n<p>To eliminate this potential liability, consider sponsoring an alcohol-free event. If, however, you do want to serve drinks at your party, consider the tips below:</p>\r\n<ol type="1">\r\n  <li>Move the party off-premises to a club or restaurant, and hold it during nonworking hours.</li>\r\n  <li>Do not conduct company business at the party - company bonus checks or presenting speeches by management could be interpreted as company business.</li>\r\n  <li>The party should be strictly and absolutely voluntary.</li>\r\n  <li>Make sure nonalcoholic drinks are available.</li>\r\n  <li>Eat...and be merry! Avoid serving salty, greasy or sweet foods which tend to make people thirsty.</li>\r\n  <li>Post your workplace substance abuse policy and address the use of alcoholic beverages in any work-related situation and office social function.</li>\r\n  <li>Designate party managers. Remind management that even at the office party, they may need to implement the company''s alcohol and substance abuse policy.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>This week, decide if you''ll be hosting a business holiday party and determine the parameters of the event if you are having one.</p>\r\n<p>To learn more about the services provided by HR Alternative Consulting, visit<a href="http://www.hralternativeconsulting.com/">http://www.hralternativeconsulting.com/</a>. Also check outÂ <a href="http://www.hrnewsmagazine.com/">http://www.hrnewsmagazine.com/</a>Â for articles about HR issues that face small business owners.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-12-02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(38, 'How did you do? The year-end company appraisal ', 'Teri Latter Director of Program Management Brillante Multicultural Marketing Group', '<p align="center">However beautiful the strategy, you should occasionally look at the results.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Winston Churchill ~</p>\r\n<p>If you''ve ever worked for a large corporation, you''ll remember that this is the time of year for the dreaded &quot;performance appraisal,&quot; when you were evaluated on what you had, and hadn''t, accomplished over the last 12 months. Now, as a business owner, you''re probably relieved that you don''t have to deal with that anymore-but, guess again. You still need to do an appraisal, only this time it''s of your company.</p>\r\n<p>Use these four steps to help you in this process:</p>\r\n<p>1.Â <strong>Evaluate your company''s results against the goals you set for the year:</strong>Â Which goals did you meet and how was that accomplished? Which ones were missed and why? Understanding where and how you excelled as well as what contributed to misses is critical in establishing your 2011 goals, strategies and tactics.</p>\r\n<p>2.Â <strong>Focus on more than just the numbers:</strong>Â While it''s easy to determine if you met your revenue or profitability goals, it''s not quite as easy to evaluate those non-number items such as company morale and customer service. But don''t let that stop you. Take the time to consider how you fared in these areas. 3.Â <strong>Do a 360 review:</strong>Â It''s important to find out how others feel about the work your company is doing. Ask a couple of clients how they feel about the work you preformed for them this year. If you have employees, get feedback from them on how the company is doing and what constructive ideas they have for the future.</p>\r\n<p>4.Â <strong>Don''t forget your long term goals:</strong>Â While the bulk of your appraisal will focus on your 2010 results, it''s an opportune time to evaluate your company''s performance in terms of your long term goals, too. How is the company tracking against that vision? Think about whether or not your results this last year moved you closer to that vision, didn''t impact it at all or actually moved you farther from it. Knowing that will help you determine if your vision is still valid or whether it needs to be tweaked. Remember that you want your 2011 goals to be in sync with and contributing to your long term plan.</p>\r\n<p>As you approach this review process, there are two things to keep in mind:</p>\r\n<p>1.Â <strong>Be brutally honest</strong>: As you evaluate your company''s performance, don''t sugarcoat the results. Only by being completely candid regarding results can you determine how best to proceed in 2011. You can'';t determine what course corrections are necessary if you don''t understand the problems you might have experienced in 2010.</p>\r\n<p>2.<strong>Don''t be humble:</strong>Â Take note of all the accomplishments of the company, too. What practices are in place that resulted in those success stories. How can you replicate your successes next year?</p>\r\n<p>Once you''ve completed this process you''ll have to tools you need for creating a well-thought out road map for 2011. You''ll know where you''re going and why. And you''ll know all the twists and turns to get there.</p>\r\n<p>This week begin the process by laying out the objectives you had for 2010 and reviewing your company''s results. Understand what contributed to those results, be they good or bad.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-12-09', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(39, 'It''s All about You ', 'Joan Spencer Licensed Acupuncturist Spencer Acupuncture Step It Up 2010 winner', '<p align="center">Some people pay more attention to their credit than they do to their own balance in life.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Catherine Pulsifer ~</p>\r\n<p>The approach of the New Year is often a time for reviewing how things went in the last year, but it''s also the time for looking forward. As we consider our New Year''s resolutions, there is one that is particularly important for both your work life and personal life- taking care of ourselves.</p>\r\n<p>As a small business owner, we wear so many hats and it can be tiring. We may be the decision makers, the marketing team, customer service representative, personnel manager, finance manager, accountant, production manager, in addition to being parent, son/daughter, friend and spouse. Or we may just wear a couple of hats. Either way it is important to be healthy. If we are not, our judgment gets clouded, mistakes are made and in general, things just don''t go right.</p>\r\n<p>So the question is how do we do this with our busy schedules? First, we have to prioritize things that we do and our health needs to be at the top. Without it so many things do not function well. With all this said, there are 3 key things that can help keep us healthy--exercise, diet and rest.</p>\r\n<p><strong>ExerciseÂ </strong>would be the biggest selling product if we could capsule the benefits of it!! When we move our bodies we literally get the blood flowing to all parts of the body. The blood carries nutrients such as oxygen to our cells and keeps our body functioning well. When selecting an exercise routine, make sure you select one that you enjoy. If there is not enjoyment, it just becomes another thing on your to do list and will usually get pushed to the bottom of the list and eventually gets eliminated. Start by selecting an activity you like such as dance, hiking, or walking and get your body moving for at least 30 minutes for a minimum of 3 times per week. So put on some music, hike a mountain or walk laps at a mall. Just get moving and life will start to flow easier.</p>\r\n<p><strong>DietÂ </strong>is one of those things that we hear about all the time. There are new fad diets all the time, but diet is not about eating one way for a certain period of time and then going back to our old habits. Diet is what we eat on a daily basis and is a lifestyle. Here are some keys to health when it comes to diet and they are: eat whole foods vs. processed foods, portion control and moderation.</p>\r\n<p>First let''s start withÂ <em>whole foods vs. processed foods</em>. In our society we have food that is readily available and is also quick and easy. The problem is that most of these foods are processed and do not include the food in its original form and therefore, are missing a lot of valuable ingredients. A lot of these foods are extracted, broken down or just plain manufactured. When you are grocery shopping look at the ingredients on the package and if there are a lot of scientific words, like mono-diglycerides vs. simple words like beans, put it back on the shelf and find a product that uses simple words.</p>\r\n<p>Next isÂ <em>portion control</em>. We should eat until we are about 70% full. If you use this rule of thumb, it prevents that overeating of products we love. Allow the body to process this food and you will find that you are satisfied more quickly than you realize.</p>\r\n<p><em>ModerationÂ </em>is the key to anything in life and our diets are no exception. Many articles have been written about the prevalence of wheat allergies today and one of the reasons for this is because we eat so much of it. You would likely be surprised at how many things contain wheat. It is in some soy sauces, salad dressings, most breads and pastas and in so many processed foods. When we eat anything to excess it can cause problems in the body, so keeping moderation in mind is the key.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Rest</strong>Â is invaluable to our health and how we operate. If we don''t get enough sleep it is hard to function and make sound decisions. For those people who have trouble sleeping, there are many options that may address it. There are herbs that can help such as chamomile, valerian or passion flower. These are very calming and can be purchased in tea, tincture or capsules. They are easy to take with little to no side effects.</p>\r\n<p>Other ways to rest our bodies are acupuncture, massage or chiropractic. These help to bring our bodies into balance which in turn relaxes us so we can sleep.</p>\r\n<p>Taking care of yourself so that you function at your best is the best gift you can give yourself. This week do a review of your exercise, diet and rest habits and determine one change you could make in each area that will contribute to a healthier you.</p>\r\n<p><strong>To learn about the services offered by Spencer Acupuncture, contact Joan at<a href="mailto:joanspencer@cox.net">joanspencer@cox.net</a></strong></p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-12-16', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(40, 'Getting the Media''s Attention ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">An expert is someone who knows some of the worst mistakes that can be made in his subject and how to avoid them.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Herbert Heisenberg</p>\r\n<p>Every day it happens. A reporter from your area of expertise needs to write a story and he needs information. Are you on his speed dial? Can he depend on you to give him the information he needs, perhaps fill in the blanks where he has no clue? Cultivating a relationship with the media takes a little effort and time but can pay off big in terms of repeated exposure and credibility. It''s time to ask yourself, what are you an expert in that you can pitch to the media?</p>\r\n<p>Media loves to use experts, so establish yourself as one. Call and introduce yourself to a reporter that covers your industry or a related field and offer to be a source whenever they may be doing a story on your industry. Make the call short and let them know you''ll follow up.</p>\r\n<p>You can follow-up with an e-mail but perhaps a more effective way to make a lasting impression is to send an &quot;expert postcard.&quot; As the name suggests, expert postcards are an oversized version of a business card that tells the reader all of your qualifications, training, special permits, and anything else that can be use to substantiate your expert claim. The postcards should be printed in high gloss color and should include your photo. You can also hand-out the postcards when you are at networking events in which reporters are present.</p>\r\n<p>After sending your initial follow-up to your media contacts, don''t be a stranger. Build a relationship and become someone that they can lean on in short notice. If they have little knowledge on the subject and don''t know how to even approach the topic, be someone they can trust.</p>\r\n<p>Check in on a regular basis. If your industry is all a buzz about a certain topic, call your media contacts and give them a heads up. Many times a reporter can''t spot the trend or its significance and it takes an expert to point it out.</p>\r\n<p>Every reporter loves having a go-to person who is accessible, full of information, and has many story ideas. In exchange for your expertise, you''ll be quoted in the media; and, since most publications are available online too, the mention of your name, company, and website will help with your page rankings on Google.</p>\r\n<p>This week, make a list of five to ten trade magazines, dailies, or weeklies that you would like to be quoted in. Pull together your qualifications and give them to a designer to create your postcard. Then, schedule time on your calendar to make those introductory calls and begin building your reputation as an expert.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-11-04', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(41, 'Look behind the Curtain ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p>Being on par in terms of price and quality only gets you in the door. Service wins the game.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Tony Alessandra</p>\r\n<p>It would seem to be a good problem to have--too many leads and not enough time to service them. You may chuckle and say &quot;wish that was my problem,&quot; but believe it or not, it does happen to small businesses that have found the key to marketing their business. So often we spend all our time rolling out the marketing program to generate leads, we don''t take the time to scrutinize the sales and delivery process that happens afterwards. Questions like these should be asked: How quickly will the prospect be called after the initial conversation? Who will manage the sales process and develop the proposal? Once the deal is signed, is there enough staff to actually deliver on the contract? Are there quality controls in place to ensure that the project is executed at the standards you expect from your company?</p>\r\n<p><em>When''s the last time you took a look behind the curtain?</em></p>\r\n<p>If you haven''t taken a look in a while, you should. Barry Moltz, Radio Host ofÂ <em>Business Insanity Talk RadioÂ </em>and frequent blogger has this to say:</p>\r\n<p>&quot;Give Great Customer Service. In a world without geographic business borders, outstanding customer service, unless you are a utility company, is the only sustainable competitive advantage. In a social-media-connected world, customer service is the new marketing.&quot;</p>\r\n<p>So in other words, if you don''t have your back-end processes working at optimum performance, then you''re customer service is likely to suffer. In today''s world, where everyone is connected, this could be a big marketing problem. Your performance on a job could either become &quot;good marketing&quot; or &quot;bad marketing&quot; once the word has hit the World Wide Web.</p>\r\n<p>Here''s how you can begin to identify where and how you can improve your back-end processes.</p>\r\n<p>1. Map out your customer relationship management (CRM) process starting with what happens after the initial call all the way to delivery. Identify potential bottle necks where resources are thin or unskilled. Mark them with red flags.</p>\r\n<p>2. Put an action plan in place for each of the red flags. Determine how much additional resource needs to be hired or purchased. Identify areas where skills need to be improved.</p>\r\n<p>3. In areas where skills need to be improved, involve your employees in the process. For each job put together a list of skills that are required to perform the role. For each skill, determine whether the person doing the job should have a low, medium, or high proficiency level. Then ask the employee to rate himself on each skill level. Look for the gaps where the employee''s self-assessed skill level is lower than your required skill level. Put an education plan in place to improve the employee''s skills in his area of weakness.</p>\r\n<p>By taking some time out to truly understand the bottlenecks and potential pitfalls in your &quot;behind the scenes&quot; processes, you are taking a proactive step to improving your customer service and building a better foundational support in which to grow your business. This week, take an hour to map out your CRM process . . . all the way to delivering the final product. As a change of pace, spend just as much time worrying about how you are going to service a customer as you do worrying about how you are going to attract a customer. You''ll see-improved service delivery will not only keep your customers coming back but will support your marketing efforts in attaining new ones, too.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-11-11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(42, '5 Steps to Building Your Social Media Coverage ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">We now have indisputable proof that online marketing, YouTube and Twitter and all that it encompasses is meaningful and has arrived.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Gene Grabowski ~</p>\r\n<p>When asked, most small business owners still have no idea of where to begin with social media. That''s completely understandable as there is a plethora of things you can do to engage in that dynamic, online world. Thanks to some help from social media guru, Mark Hayward (<a href="http://www.mark-hayward.com/">www.mark-hayward.com</a>), here are the steps that will help any do-it-yourself, social media newbie penetrate the world of online, social communities.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Step 1: Determine your social media goals</strong></p>\r\n<p>Blog traffic, new content, retweets, likes, bookmarks, subscriptions, conversions--all admirable goals to set and work hard to attain. However, no matter what you''re end goal is, there is one goal that we all strive for . . . increasing social media footprint. Read on to learn how you can reach more potential prospects online.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Step 2: Do your prep work</strong></p>\r\n<p>Research key words for your business. These will be needed for profile set-ups, your blogs, comments, and articles - you want the search engines finding your stuff when web browsers have questions.</p>\r\n<p>Setup your listening strategy with Google Alerts for your keywords-see who else is chatting out there.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Step 2: Show Your Expertise</strong></p>\r\n<p>Start a blog (use free tools--WordPress or Blogger).</p>\r\n<p>Brainstorm and come up with blog post ideas that you can create full posts from later.</p>\r\n<p>Read a lot of others'' blogs. This will get you in the habit of searching for relevant information, which could lead to commenting, which could expand your footprint.</p>\r\n<p>Visit and comment on forums and blogs that cover your niche.</p>\r\n<p>Write a guest post or two on someone else''s blog.</p>\r\n<p>Search newspapers for articles on your niche and leave comments.</p>\r\n<p>Join Help-A-Reporter and reply to some inquiries.</p>\r\n<p>Compose a freely downloadable e-Book that is incredibly useful. Offer it everywhere-your blog, others'' blogs, your newsletter, LinkedIn, Facebook.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Step 3: Get the word out</strong></p>\r\n<p>Email your friends and let them know your social media profiles.</p>\r\n<p>Add your web URL, Facebook, LinkedIn, and Twitter to your email signature.</p>\r\n<p>Write a press release about your business and look at tools like pitchengine.com which connects to readers, bloggers, and journalists all at one time.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Step 4: Try new things</strong></p>\r\n<p>Create a Flickr account and upload some photos.</p>\r\n<p>Create profiles on StumbleUpon, DIGG, and Reddit</p>\r\n<p>Create a Squiddo page-;your own personal web page to pitch your expertise</p>\r\n<p><strong>Step 5: Stay active on the tried and true</strong></p>\r\n<p>Use LinkedIn to continue to manage your business network and stay in front of them. Be sure to join groups and engage in discussion.</p>\r\n<p>Don''t underestimate the power of Facebook for business-keep adding your business friends too.</p>\r\n<p>Join Twitter-listen, learn, and engage in conversation.</p>\r\n<p>This week, pick three to five items on this list and tackle them. Be sure to schedule 20 minutes every day on your calendar for your social media activities. Keep at it for three weeks and then stand back and count your results.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-11-18', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
