(43, 'A Strong Contact Database Means Falling out of Love with Magical Soutions', 'Dr. Bob Wright, CEO, Wright Business Institute, Sales Coach', '<p align="center">&quot;A complex system that works is invariably found to have evolved from a simple system that works.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">~John Gall</p>\r\n<p>Many small business owners get very excited about their first major undertaking when setting up their contact database. After years of living off of no data or patched together data, the contact database running on a fun, new software application can appear like the oasis in the desert.</p>\r\n<p>But these same owners and entrepreneurs can quickly fall out of love with their solutions as the rubber meets the road on implementation.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Keep it simple to start</strong></p>\r\n<p>What many of us fail to remember is that a solid system starts simply. Don''t bite off the entire universe of contact relationship management. A simple but well implemented first step allows you to build upon it. A complex system that is too overwhelming and you and your employees don''t follow, will never be a solid foundation for any contact management system.</p>\r\n<p>Identify the most business-critical elements you need to track. Clearly having one place where your customer''s contact information resides is essential, but what is the next piece of critical functionality that you need in order for your business to take a major step forward. Don''t worry about automating everything. Identify a few key areas and set up a plan to have them impeccably implemented over the next six months to a year, then follow up from there.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Consistency is key</strong>Â If you and your employees are not good at following your manual systems consistently, the odds that you will magically transform your habits because of a new software system is not likely. As you identify the few simple steps you will take in your phase one implementation, include a plan for rewarding consistency and make yourself a part of it. Use your weekly staff meetings to identify problems and brainstorm creative solutions. For example, you may choose to focus on logging sales calls to your customers in your first phase implementation but soon realize that many of these calls are made in the car without the ability to look into any electronic system. Use your staff time to brainstorm solutions to this. Maybe your salesperson can call the office and have a receptionist open the system and log in the information received verbally for the salesperson. Or perhaps they can leave themselves a voicemail with the data and enter it later that evening.</p>\r\n<p>The bottom line is that a simple, consistent approach that is well-tested will give you a wonderful foundation for future phases. But a complex un-tested approach will cause everyone involved to resent or abandon any well-intentioned system.</p>\r\n<p>This week, identify what your phase one contact database needs to contain and work towards its implementation. If you already have a system in place, pick one area you''d like to focus on improving in the next six months.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-10-14', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(44, 'Pricing: Three Common Mistakes Entrepreneurs Make', 'Rich Lyons, Finance Coach, Lyons Consulting Adjunct Instructor, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;A man must be big enough to admit his mistakes, smart enough to profit from them, and strong enough to correct them.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">~John C. Maxwell</p>\r\n<p>As a small business owner in a tough economy you are probably doing what others are doing-whatever it takes to stay afloat as your clients cut back on their purchases. But when it comes to setting a price for your product or service, there are three mistakes you can''t afford to make or you''ll no longer be hanging out your shingle.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mistake #1 Not Getting Enough DataÂ </strong>When establishing pricing for a product or service, many small business owners don''t gather enough data to include in their price setting decision. It''s important to take into account the fully loaded cost of the product or service. Shipping costs, materials, credit card charges can add up quickly to strip you of any profit and to keep you from getting ahead. Be sure to include your time in the delivery of the product as well. Many entrepreneurs forget that their time is valuable. And include commissions and other costs of selling.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mistake #2 Focusing on Revenue vs. Profit</strong>Â What profit do you intend to generate from the product? If you only look at the revenue you''ll gain from the pricing of your product or service then your short-sightedness will catch up with you quicker than you think. A small profit margin means you won''t have the resources you need to keep your business growing. Small business owners often think they''ll make up for this gap later, but the reality is that later never comes. This may impact how you structure your payment schedule as well. In order to improve cash flow, you should try to collect enough upfront or early in the project to pay for your costs. Remember, if you need to borrow to fund a project, it costs you money as well.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mistake #3 Failing to Create Additional Value</strong>Â What can you do to set apart your product or service that isn''t completely price dependent? Often, small business owners will think that they have to be the lowest priced option available because they don''t hold the value of what they offer or they don''t creatively brainstorm ways to add value to their product or service. What is unique about you vs. your competitors? How can you more clearly communicate this value to your prospective clients so that they are not simply looking at the price of your product or service in their buying decision? You need to truly understand their business needs and become their trusted advisor. Then they won''t think twice about paying you more.</p>\r\n<p>If you''ve already made one of these mistakes, never fear. There is always an opportunity to try something new. This week, set aside some time to do a quick review of your pricing policies to make sure that you are on track for long term growth.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-10-21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(45, 'Supersize your Business: Thinking Big when Planning for Business Growth ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">Without continual growth and progress, such words as improvement, achievement, and success have no meaning.</p>\r\n<p align="center">Benjamin Franklin</p>\r\n<p>While growth can happen incrementally through the natural progression of your business, unplanned growth can result in unprofitable growth. If you''ve made the conscious decision to grow your business beyond its current state, then you need to take the time to plan for that growth.</p>\r\n<p>Small business consultant, Michael Walsh of Kaizen Consulting states that most entrepreneurs don''t realize that it is better to double or even triple your business instead of consistently growing it by 15% every year. Initially, you may think his notion is a crazy one, but read on to understand his logic.</p>\r\n<p>When businesses grow slowly, they don''t take into account how they are taxing their current staff and resources. They simply pile on more. Their people get tired, mistakes start to occur, customer satisfaction declines, and owners begin to wonder if it''s worth it to try and grow at all. However, if you know you are going to double or triple, then you can plan for the expansion of your infrastructure and your staff. You don''t delude yourself into thinking that your existing structures are going to continue to work, so you make plans to increase staff, improve accounting systems, increase marketing support materials attune with higher levels of growth.</p>\r\n<p>This doesn''t mean you need to spend a lot of money as soon as you''ve decided to grow. But what it does mean is you need to put some careful thought into how your organization is going to look at a much larger size, let''s say $3M in sales. The easiest way to do this is to imagine your organization chart at $3M. Before drawing out a proposed organization chart for a much larger company, you need to ask yourself some important questions: How will your business operate at a larger size? How will you deliver your goods and services to your customers? Will you need to open up more locations? Where would those locations be? How will they be staffed and how will decisions be made?</p>\r\n<p>Next you need to project the financial picture of your large firm. In most cases, growing your business will require investment in money and resources. How will your assets need to grow to support the growth? How will you fund the expansion? What will your future income statement look like?</p>\r\n<p>Once you''ve done your homework for your business growth at $3M, ratchet it back to a reasonable &quot;next phase&quot; growth and develop your transition plan, outlining the your staffing, infrastructure, and funding needs. As Mr. Walsh preaches, now you'';ll have the right mindset to make decisions that won''t compromise your customer service, your employee retention, or your infrastructure overload. By thinking through your $3M picture first, you''ll have increased your chances to generate a truly integrated plan that will be much easier to achieve.</p>\r\n<p>This week, set aside some time to think about how your organization would look at three times its size. Not only is it an exciting exercise, but a very necessary one for planning profitable growth.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-10-28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(46, 'Staying on Track with Good Communications ', 'Teri Latter Director of Program Management Brillante Multicultural Group', '<p align="center">To succeed, you will soon learn, as I did, the importance of a solid foundation in the basics of education--literacy, both verbal and numerical, and communication skills.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Alan Greenspan~</p>\r\n<p>As a project manager at a Fortune 500 company, I had a slogan: On time, on spec, on budget. Now that I'';m at a smaller firm, I find I still manage projects with that slogan in mind. In fact, it''s probably even more important at firms where resources are limited and a single project can make or break a company.</p>\r\n<p>In a smaller company, a project can range from installing service at a new customer''s location to moving from your home office to a new address. No matter what the task is, there is one key ingredient needed to assure success: good communication. A recent study conducted by VitalSmarts and Concurs Group indicates that without effective communications, any plan or project will fail 85% of the time. Put good communications in place and that failure rate can be reduced by 50-70%.</p>\r\n<p>When the success of a project depends not just on you, but on others working with you, be they employees, contractors or people at another firm, then it''s time to put your communications skills to work. Here are five tips that can help bring your project in on time, on spec and on budget:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Determine your team</strong>: Do a mental visualization of all the pieces of your project from beginning to end to be sure that you''ve included everyone who will play a part in bringing it to fruition.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Fact-based planning</strong>: Here''s where communications really kicks in. You need input from everyone involved in order to determine realistic deadlines, budgets and deliverables. Go ahead and be aggressive, but stay within the realm of possibility if you want buy-in. Remember, especially when working with contractors, they aren''t just sitting waiting for your business; they have other projects, too, and that will impact when they can complete yours.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Establish accountability</strong>: Be sure that everyone you are working with understands that they are accountable for the results in their area. Document the expectations and share them with everyone so there are no misunderstandings.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>On-going dialogue</strong>: While you''ve made others accountable for delivering, you can''t just hand it off and assume all will be well. Regular dialogue with all members will help you see if issues are coming up that can derail the project and allow you to address them before that happens. If your project is big enough, you may want to set up a standing meeting for this purpose.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Positive reinforcement:</strong>Â Let those you are working with know you appreciate their work as you go along. It''s a simple but often overlooked action that can make a difference in people''s performance. Whether they are employees or not, someone who knows that you value what they are doing will more likely be willing to go that extra mile on the project when needed.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>This week, think of something you are working on, or planning, that involves three or more people to execute. Go through these steps and see the difference it can make in your end result.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-09-02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(47, 'The Four Steps to Collecting Late Payments ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach, CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">You can take a chance on any man who pays his bills on time. ~ Terence ~ Roman writer</p>\r\n<p>One thing many business owners dread is dealing with unpaid invoices and collecting money from customers. However, if ignored, the stakes are high and collection becomes more and more unlikely. So what should you do? Here are four steps to follow when you face this unfortunate, but common, situation.</p>\r\n<p>1. Give them the benefit of the doubt</p>\r\n<p>Don''t burn any bridges. Call your contact at the company and make sure that the nonpayment is not an oversight. Ask if they need a copy of their last invoice or if they would like to make payment arrangements. Sometimes it really is a matter of forgetting the due date or losing the invoice in a pile of papers or e-mails. Important:; be sure to make this call or send this friendly reminder just a few days after the original due date-<em>don''t wait.</em></p>\r\n<p>2. Send a formal letter</p>\r\n<p>If you''ve sent a friendly reminder and your customer still hasn''t paid, you need to send a more formal letter. Make sure to keep a non-confrontational tone, reminding the customer that the payment is overdue and give information on what methods of payments you accept. Keep a copy of this letter for your records.</p>\r\n<p>3. Send a certified letter</p>\r\n<p>If you still receive no payment or no response from the customer, you need to send a letter via certified mail. This helps you prove that your customer received your letter.</p>\r\n<p>4. Take action</p>\r\n<p>If you can''t collect your payment after friendly reminders, payment request letters, and a certified notice of late payment, you may have to take action. You can file a claim in small claims court if it is not a large account. You may not need an attorney if you can prepare your claim on your own. Or, you can contact a collection agency. Often times they only charge if they collect and they can receive upwards to one-third of the amount outstanding.</p>\r\n<p>Of course, it''s preferable to not have to chase down late payments at all. Sometimes adjusting your company guidelines on when product is shipped in regards to payment can improve your outstanding A/R significantly. Here are four things you can do to decrease your unpaid accounts:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Don''t ship merchandise until you''ve been paid if you have a product-based business.</li>\r\n  <li>Get a deposit before you provide any services if you have a service-based business.</li>\r\n  <li>Clearly state your policies regarding late payment on your website and invoices.</li>\r\n  <li>List a clearly-marked payment date on your invoice so customers don''t miss it.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-09-16', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(48, 'Building Your Email Database ', 'Teri Latter Director of Program Management Brillante Multicultural Marketing Group', '<p align="center">I want fresh contacts, more vital searching.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Emily Carr</p>\r\n<p>You want to send out a newsletter or even just an occasional email to let people know about your company, but your database of emails is pretty skimpy. What can you do to beef it up? Here are some easy-to-implement ideas that will help you grow that database and increase your reach to customers and potential customers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Current email contacts:Â </strong>Go through your email directory and gather contacts whom you want to receive your information. Don''t forget to get contacts from others in your company, too.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Existing and potential customers:</strong>Â They may be in your email directory, but if they''re not, be sure to include your current customers on your list. Also, add the email of anyone who is a current or past potential customer.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Business cards:Â </strong>If you''ve received a business card from someone and it has an email on it, then you can add them to your list. Be sure to get cards at every networking event you attend, at trade shows, and meetings. Again, if your partner or sales person is out there gathering cards, be sure to include them into your database.</p>\r\n<p><strong>On your website:Â </strong>If you''re sending out a newsletter, be sure to have a &quot;Sign up for our newsletter&quot; button on your website. Most email vendors make it easy for you to add this to your site.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Your email footer:Â </strong>Once you have that button on your site, then add a note to your email signature such as, &quot;To sign up for our newsletter, visit us at www. yourwebsite.com&quot;. Make sure all employees do the same. Once someone requests your newsletter, you''ll have their email address.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Forward to a Friend:</strong>Â On your newsletter, be sure to include a &quot;Forward to a Friend&quot; button. Consider incenting your readers to forward it on&amp;-many email providers enable you to see who has forwarded your email.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Your blog:</strong>If you blog, include a link to your email or website on the blog.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Contests:</strong>Â If you''re exhibiting at a trade show or other event, run a contest or a raffle and make a requirement for entry that they provide a business card or email address.</p>\r\n<p>As you can see, there are myriad opportunities for getting those email addresses that you want. This week, try implementing one of these ideas and see how many new email addresses you are able to add to your database.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-09-30', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(49, 'Understanding the Hard-to-Handle Employee ', 'Michelle Binks President, HR Consulting Solutions', '<p align="center">&quot;If I could know me, I could know the universe.&quot; ~Shirley Maclaine</p>\r\n<p>From time to time, we all have difficult employees or situations arise with employees that need to be addressed. Consider this: Is that employee a difficult employee? Are they in the correct position? Or is it their personality? Having too many of one personality in a company or department can hinder productivity greatly. Personality plays a huge part in who a person is and what position is best for them within an organization. Keeping two things in mind can help you navigate these situations better:</p>\r\n<p><em>1. Understanding Personalities</em>. Many times managers feel as if they have a difficult employee or someone who is not performing up to the managers standards when in actuality the manager doesn''t understand that person''s personality.</p>\r\n<p>Going back to Dr. Bob'';s presentation on personality types, personalities play a huge role in the workplace. Understanding your personality and that of the people around you is very important as a business owner and manager.</p>\r\n<p>For example, many entrepreneurs or managers are &quot;Regulators.&quot; They''re focused on the outcome and the big picture. When they have an &quot;Analyzer&quot; for an employee, they might find that person to be someone that they always need to assign project due date to, otherwise the &quot;Analyzer&quot; will complete the project on his or her time, when they have had time to carefully analyze everything and sort through the details and facts. Because of this, they tend to be a &quot;steady as you go&quot; type of employee and are many times viewed as someone who doesn''t produce. In actuality, it might take them a little longer to complete the project than a &quot;Regulator&quot;, but it is usually error free.</p>\r\n<p>2.<em>Determining the</em>Â <em>Correct Position for a Personality.</em>Â Many times employers put good employees in to open positions because they feel they will do a good job; unfortunately, this can sometimes be a mistake. For example, an &quot;Energizer&quot; is someone who likes social activity, excitement, and change. They may be a great employee but their personality is not one that is so worried about accuracy and follow-through. An &quot;Energizer&quot; is probably not the best person to have running your finance department. Ensuring you have the right personality fit for the position will not only ensure the success of your employee but it will further the success of your business.</p>\r\n<p>If you haven''t done so already, take Dr. Bob''s personality quiz. It will better help you determine your personality, the personality(s) of those working around you and how best to manage those personalities.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-08-05', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(50, 'Ask and You Shall Receive--Referrals, that is! ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Growth Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;If there is something to gain and nothing to lose by asking, by all means ask!&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">--W. Clement Stone</p>\r\n<p>People would rather do business with someone they know, or were referred to, than with strangers. That''s a simple fact. In fact, for the buyer, a referral removes a level of risk, because someone you know has already used this person''s product or services.</p>\r\n<p>Then why is it that even the most advanced salesperson doesn''t ask for referrals as often as they should? Two main barriers face most of us each and every day.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Limiting beliefs</strong>Â Many of us have limiting beliefs that get in the way of our asking for things. We are probably not even aware of these beliefs, because they operate unconsciously within us. We may believe that it'';s rude or selfish to ask for things or that we don''t deserve it or that people don''t really want to help us. We don'';t realize it, but these beliefs keep us from the simple process of asking for that referral.</p>\r\n<p><strong>A System for Referrals</strong>Â Even if you have had success asking for referrals, you may not be maximizing your sales potential because you don''t have a system set up to remind you to do ask. There are certain checkpoints that you can put in place to help with your system. For example, every time you get a compliment from a customer, you can use that as cue to ask for a referral. You can also set up the system up front and ask people, if you do a good job for them, would they be willing to refer you. Another simple, but powerful tool, is to use whatever spreadsheet or system you use to keep track of your sales activity and add a column for referrals. Simply seeing the reminder will help you remember to ask for more.</p>\r\n<p>Think about how much more business you could do by simply asking for referrals from your satisfied customers. This week, ask for one referral you might not have otherwise.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-08-19', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(51, 'Message in a Box ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach CEO, Hi-Impact marketing & Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">All prosperity begins in the mind and is dependent only upon the full use of our creative imagination. ~ Ruth Ross ~</p>\r\n<p>Over the years, the response rate on direct mail has declined and marketers have turned to online strategies for lower costs and better returns. However, an online-only approach can be very limiting and produce diminishing returns, too. Direct mail still has a place in the overall marketing plan. One particular type, dimensional mail or mail-in-a-box, might be just what you need to get noticed.</p>\r\n<p>A can of Red Bull wrapped with a customized label . . . &quot;Let us give your brand a boost.&quot;</p>\r\n<p>A pack of chewing game in a customized box . . . &quot;Chew on this idea.&quot;</p>\r\n<p>It can be as easy as using regular household items to cleverly depict your message. Once you have your concept, simply work with your graphic designer to create a label or stickers to communicate your message and customize your box. Avoid promotional giveaways like a coffee mug that are commonly found in everyone''s office or home.</p>\r\n<p>When launching a dimensional mail campaign, keep these three tips in mind:</p>\r\n<p>1.Â <em>Use a small, prequalified list</em>. The cost of dimensional mail is significantly higher than flat mail, so target only your best prospects and make sure you have their correct contact information. Make a few phone calls first to ensure you are targeting decision makers only.</p>\r\n<p>2.Â <em>Communicate your competitive edge</em>. Not only should your dimensional mail be creative and clever, it should clearly community your &quot;one unique benefit&quot; that sets you apart from your competition.</p>\r\n<p>3.Â <em>Follow-up immediately</em>. Don''t mail out so many boxes that you can''t make a phone call to each and every one of them upon delivery. An effective dimensional mail piece will warm up prospects and make them more receptive to your phone call.</p>\r\n<p>When designing your marketing plan, consider if dimensional mail might be a component in your integrated plan of online newsletters, sales calls, and PR. If you''re having trouble &quot;breaking through,&quot; dimensional mail may just be the tool you need.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-07-01', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(52, 'Please Open Me: A Newsletter''s Plea ', 'Teri Latter Director of Program Management Brillante Multicultural Marketing Group', '<p align="center">&quot;Many attempts to communicate are nullified by saying too much.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Robert Greenleaf ~</p>\r\n<p>We''re all familiar with the &quot;gatekeeper&quot; - the person in the office that you have to talk your way past in order to speak with the decision-maker. In today''s electronic world, we face the same issue but in a different way . . . how do we get the recipients to open our newsletter so that we can &quot;talk&quot; to them?</p>\r\n<p>Here are some ideas on how to increase that all-important open-rate:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>The From Label:</strong>Â Be sure that your &quot;From&quot; label reflects newsletter they are receiving.<em>ABC''s Weekly TipsÂ </em>orÂ <em>News from XYZ Company</em>Â should remind the receiver that they signed up for your newsletter and make them more likely to open it. In most cases, you will not want to just use your email address as your recipients may or may not have met you. Your From label should remain consistent each time you send your newsletter</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Subject Line:Â </strong>Experts in the business are constantly trying to develop the formula for the perfect subject line, a feat no one can ever really accomplish given the wide variances in the kinds of businesses that are out there. There are, however, some &quot;best&quot; practices that will work for most any newsletter:</li>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><em>Your subject line must relate to the content of the newsletter</em>. Subject lines that are too cute or not related to the content of your newsletter may get someone to open once, but after that, they''ll know better! In addition, if the subject line is not related to your content, you''ll be in violation of CAN-SPAM rules.</li>\r\n    <li><em>Test your subject line</em>. Depending on the size of your list, consider splitting your list and then use a different subject line with each list. One might be more general while the other is more specific, or one might emphasize one aspect of your newsletter (something new in the industry) vs. another (new products you are rolling out). Which type of subject line draws best for you? Let that guide you for future subject lines.</li>\r\n    <li><em>Keep your subject line to about 50 characters</em>. It needs to be short and attention-grabbing. If you can''t say it in 50 characters, chances are that it''s neither.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Content:</strong>Â Consumers and businesses alike are inundated with email and are only going to check out those that appear to have some value for them. If they opened yours once and didn''t find it relevant, they''re not likely to open it again. Consider including the following:</li>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>An informational article about: new developments in the industry, ways to use your product to drive revenue for the client, market trends and other items the reader might not know about</li>\r\n    <li>Info about upcoming events you are holding or attending; if you''re a guest speaker somewhere, include that information. You can also provide info on industry events</li>\r\n    <li>A coupon or other incentive to contact you</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>As you think about your newsletter, put yourself in your client''s shoes. Does the newsletter pass the &quot;so what?&quot; test? If it does, then you''ve just increased the odds that they''ll keep opening up the ones they get from you in the future.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted</em>.</p>', '', '', '2010-07-08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(53, 'Hire What You Desire ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Growth Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;Sales are contingent upon the attitude of the salesman - not the attitude of the prospect.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">~W. Clement Stone</p>\r\n<p>Hiring the right people with the right attributes is critical to your success and your culture. Just because you like a potential employee or because they fit in with your culture does not mean they can or will sell. On the other hand, just because a potential candidate can sell well does not mean they will fit in with your culture or that you will feel supported by them.</p>\r\n<p>Your first job in hiring is to lead by example in diving into your role as a salesperson for your small business. It will be nearly impossible to hire a candidate when you are not stretching yourself to sell. In fact, it will be too easy to buy a good pitch from someone who doesn''t have the substance behind the flash. On the other hand, when you are living the life of a salesperson, you will definitely be able to sense the real thing when you meet him or her. Here are 3 quick tips for hiring a successful sales person.</p>\r\n<p>1.Â <strong>Think through your culture.Â </strong>Before you begin your interview, take a little time to think through the culture you are creating at your organization. Get clear on those attributes so that you can probe to see if the person you are speaking to is likely to thrive in your environment.</p>\r\n<p>2.Â <strong>Get specific on sales activity.</strong>Â Next, be prepared to ask very specific questions on the potential candidate''s past sales activity. Discover what metrics they track, how they track them, etc. A strong seller will be able to tell you exactly what their systems are and what their past successes and failures have been-in very specific terms. If they are being vague, you can trust that you will never feel secure in the activity they are generating for your business.</p>\r\n<p>3.Â <strong>Consider trying out the candidate.Â </strong>Finally, consider a trial hire and make sure that you have set up their compensation in a way that they must bring in business in order to earn their place in the organization. A salesperson looking for a set salary does not intend to drive revenue for your business.</p>\r\n<p>This week, whether you are currently hiring a salesperson or intend to do so in the future, take some time to make some notes about your ideal candidate as well as a list of sample questions you could use in an interview.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-07-22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(54, 'An Easy Answer to "What do you do?" ', 'Barbara Lopez President, Brightfarm Introductions', '<p align="left">The difference between the right word and the almost right word is the difference between lightning and lightning bug. ~ Mark Twain ~ Have you ever been asked the very simple question &quot;What do you do?&quot; andthen completely drawn a blank?This can be a frustrating scenario because youÂ <strong>know</strong>Â what you do, but how do you take everything that''s great about who you are and what you offer and condense it down to a clear and concise answer to that question?</p>\r\n<p>There are a lot of common reasons why people freeze up when asked that question - which one(s) resonate with you:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>the inability to articulate quickly and simply what you do</li>\r\n  <li>the worry that you''ll end up going &quot;on and on&quot;, resulting in the other person losing interest</li>\r\n  <li>the worry that they won''t understand what you do</li>\r\n  <li>the worry that the other person won''t want to know more</li>\r\n  <li>the worry that people will make a pre-conceived judgment about the industry you are in</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>As you can see, most of these areÂ <strong>worries</strong>, and that only adds pressure to answering the question. Instead of worrying, let''s look at a simple way to determine how to answer that question - it''s a &quot;formula&quot; that is easy to personalize for you and your business.</p>\r\n<p>When asked, &quot;What do you do?&quot; simply respond with:</p>\r\n<p><em>&quot;Well, you know how some people (or target niche: business professionals, entrepreneurs, consumers, women in business, etc.) haveÂ <strong>[insert a common problem here]</strong>?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Pause and wait for acknowledgment. (They''ll either nod or say &quot;yes&quot;. Hopefully, they themselves have that problem.)</em></p>\r\n<p><em>&quot;Well, what I do isÂ <strong>[insert solution here]</strong>.&quot;</em></p>\r\n<p>Let''s look at an example of how I use this formula for what I do as The Elevator Pitch Coach:</p>\r\n<p><em>&quot;<strong>Well, you know howÂ </strong>some business professionals spend a lot of time networking and will have to sometimes give a networking commercial or &quot;elevator pitch&quot; to an entire roomful of people . . . and they sometimes don''t know what to say?&quot;</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Pause and wait for acknowledgment. (They''ll either nod or say &quot;yes&quot;.)</em></p>\r\n<p><strong><em>&quot;Well, what I do isÂ </em></strong><em>teach professionals a 4-step process for developing their elevator pitch so that they DO know what to say when networking or promoting their business.&quot;</em></p>\r\n<p>The key is to be short and sweet and, best of all, simple. Because I only answered their question and didn''t give them a big list of my various services or HOW I do it, this naturally opens the conversation up more by them asking, &quot;How do you do that?&quot;</p>\r\n<p>Take this simple formula and apply it to yourself and what you do in your business to create your own quick answer to the question &quot;What do you do?&quot; and see how it can help calm your networking nerves while boosting your introduction at the same time.</p>\r\n<p><em>Barbara Lopez, &quot;The Elevator Pitch Coach&quot; with Brightfarm Introductions, teaches business professionals a simple 4-step process on how to introduce themselves with high impact so that they stand out and are remembered.</em></p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-06-03', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(55, 'Does your Business Have a Bumper Sticker?', 'Michelle Lanter Smith CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">The very essence of leadership is that you have to have a vision. It''s got to be a vision you articulate clearly and forcefully on every occasion.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Theodore Hesburgh ~ President, University of Notre Dame</p>\r\n<p>When you see a bumper sticker on the back of a car, you can get a glimpse of what the driver stands for in a quick instant. Your brain makes a connection and a judgment is made. &quot;Right on,&quot; &quot;How stupid,&quot; or &quot;Who Cares?&quot; Each represents a different opinion and each represents a view point or a positioning in your mind of that driver.</p>\r\n<p>Your business needs to make a connection with your potential fans out there, too-a bumper sticker for your business can do just the trick. It represents your brand identity or the unique benefit that you provide to your customers. By clearly stating what makes you unique, you separate yourself from your competitors, making it easier for the buyer to create a connection to your business.</p>\r\n<p>Your bumper sticker differs from your elevator pitch in that the elevator pitch has one primary use, answering the &quot;What do you do&quot; question, while your bumper sticker can serve various purposes. You might post it on your website, it can become your slogan, or you might just use it internally to help you keep focused on what your company is about.</p>\r\n<p>To be effective, your bumper stick should directly communicate or imply these three things:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>The service or product you offer</li>\r\n  <li>Your target audience</li>\r\n  <li>Your unique benefit</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Take the time to schedule 15 minutes this week to work on your business''s identity. First write down five of your strengths that have value in your customer''s eye. Identify the strength that is the most unique and brings the ultimate value to your customer. Then couple that strength with your target audience-the fan base that you want to go after. Now sleep on it; go back to your daily routine, but continue to test your unique strength when you speak to a customer or prospect that resides in your desired fan base. If you like how it feels, you may just have the basis of your identity statement.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-06-10', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(56, 'Who is Draining your Business and Who''s Making Money for You? ', 'Rich Lyons, Finance Coach Lyons Consulting Adjunct Instructor, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;Signing them is one thing, but bringing them to profitability is another.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Don McMahan</p>\r\n<p>Do you know which customers are making you the greatest margin per dollar spent?</p>\r\n<p>If you''re like most small business owners, you probably know which clients drive your overall revenue but you probably haven''t taken the time to analyze which customers are driving your profits. If you haven''t taken this important step, now is the time.</p>\r\n<p>Here''s how:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>List your clients by revenue and direct expenses.</li>\r\n  <li>Subtract the direct expenses from revenue to see what your gross margin is per client.</li>\r\n  <li>Now rank order your clients from highest to lowest gross margin percentage.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Once you''ve done this, you can begin to ask yourself about the implications of their rankings. What impact does this quick glance have for your marketing, sales, and pricing model? Are there certain customers that you should be investing more time in developing? Are there are clients that take a lot of time and attention but who really don''t contribute to your bottom line?</p>\r\n<p>This week, set aside time to do this analysis. The insights you have could make the difference between subsisting and thriving for your business.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-06-17', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(57, 'Go for the No', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;An objection is not a rejection; it is simply a request for more information.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">--Bo Bennett</p>\r\n<p>Too often sales people, small business owners, and entrepreneurs accept the resistance that their customers give them. They take their objections seriously and fail to even ask for the business.</p>\r\n<p>At the Wright Business Institute, one of the most successful sales contests we run in our sales groups is a contest called &quot;Going for the No.&quot; In this contest, the salesperson who wins is the one who gets the most rejections- the most &quot;No&quot;s.</p>\r\n<p>To the surprise of many, this contest often yields the greatest sales results for the participants who engage in it. Why? When a salesperson goes for getting as many rejections as they can, they also get far more sales and closed business deals than they expected. Through the contest, they do not shy away from the objections. As a result, they end up asking for more business. Yes, they hear a lot of No, but they also hear a lot more Yes than they typically would.</p>\r\n<p>People begin to realize that there is much more business out there and more possibilities available if only they will learn to move through their customers'' objections.</p>\r\n<p>This week, see how many refusals you can get and, through that experience, how many more closes you can have as well. You''ll be delighted to discover that there is a whole world of revenue available beyond your customers'' front line resistance.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-06-24', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(58, 'How do I love leads? Let me count the ways. ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">Quality is never an accident. It is always the result of an intelligent effort.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~John Ruskin~</p>\r\n<p>Do you know where your leads are coming from? How many ways do you currently generate leads? If you''re not sure, count them.</p>\r\n<p>Do you have a website that captures information? A referral system? E-tips? Pay per click? Networking events? The Yellow pages? Direct response advertising?</p>\r\n<p>There are endless ways to generate leads but unless we are aware of the methods we use and evaluate them based on effectiveness, we''ll just spin in circles and waste our time, energy, and resources.</p>\r\n<p>List at least 3 to 5 lead generating methodologies that you want to evaluate over the next 3 months. Keep track of how much each of these methods costs you to manage. What do you pay in time or resources to use these methods? Also track how much revenue you generated out of each of these. At the end of 3 months, rank order your lead generating methodologies from most effective to least effective (in results) and from most cost effective to least cost effective.</p>\r\n<p>Use this as an evaluation tool to let go of methodologies that no longer make sense and to add in some new methodologies to test out.</p>\r\n<p>Remember, there are endless ways to generate leads, but you need to be constantly experimenting and evaluating to discover the best bang for buck.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.'' Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-05-06', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(59, 'Who knows you best? ', 'Teri Latter Director of Program Management Brillante Multicultural Marketing', '<p align="center">Your most unhappy customers are your greatest source of learning.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Bill Gates~</p>\r\n<p>As you are working to better define your optimum product offering and target market, you are undoubtedly looking at your competitors and researching their products on the internet. That''s certainly an important step, but if you stop there, you''ve stopped short. You need to talk to those who really know about your product or service . . . your customers.</p>\r\n<p>Are you struggling to understand how you are better than your competition? Ask your customers how you stack up. Are there areas where they believe you outshine the competition? Are there areas where you don''t hold a match to the competition? Hearing how your customers answer those questions can help you define the niche you should be serving both in terms of products and customers.</p>\r\n<p>Ask your customer what they think your strengths are and then look at how you''ve been positioning your company. Do they see your greatest asset as being superior customer service, but you''ve been touting low prices? Maybe you should be re-thinking how you communicate your value to potential customers.</p>\r\n<p>While you''re at it, find out what they think your weaknesses are. If you''re missing a product or service they need, explore the opportunity. If there''s a quality issue with what you offer, evaluate what impact improving the quality would have on future sales.</p>\r\n<p>This week, think about 3-4 specific questions you would like to ask your customers to help you get closer to understanding how to position your company and its offerings. Then consider asking another small business owner if they would be willing to call a couple of your customers to get this information . . . and you, of course, will return the favor.</p>\r\n<p>Whether you''re running a one-person operation or a multi-million dollar corporation, itÂ <em>always</em>Â pays to listen to the customer.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-05-13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
INSERT INTO `etips` (`id`, `title`, `author`, `body`, `metakeywords`, `metadescription`, `created`, `modified`) VALUES
(60, 'Rapport or Results?', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Growth Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;Know thyself.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center"><em>~ Plato ~</em></p>\r\n<p>When it comes to rapport, sales people fall somewhere on a continuum. One the one side you have those who establish great rapport, have a wonderful time and never close business. On the other, you have those who have terrible rapport and miss a lot of details because they fail to establish credibility and a strong relationship.</p>\r\n<p>In the sweet spot are those who establish great rapport, get high quality information, establish deep partnerships with clients and create an ever-expanding client base that brings them both profit and personal satisfaction.</p>\r\n<p>But how do you establish this kind of rapport? You have to know yourself and know your prospects. You need to remember that we all have different personalities and therefore different ways we view the world.</p>\r\n<p>Maybe you enjoy the energy and excitement that comes with talking about big visionary stuff, and you couldn''t care less about the details. If your prospect is someone who loves analysis and details then you could in advertently miss the mark in establishing rapport.</p>\r\n<p>This week, take the personality profile assessment, found in theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Coaches Forum</a>Â in the Business Growth Strategies Forum, to identify your personality profile. Then be sure to tune in to the webinar on Tuesday, May 25, so that you can learn more about the impacts of your personality on your sales.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-05-20', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(61, 'Are you afraid of your P&L?', 'Rich Lyons, Finance Coach Lyons ConsultingAdjunct Instructor The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;To state the facts frankly is not to despair the future nor indict the past.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ John F. Kennedy ~</p>\r\n<p>One of the biggest challenges that beginning entrepreneurs face is measuring and tracking their financials on a regular basis which includes producing and reviewing the Profit and Loss statement. Think of your monthly profit and loss statement as the score of a basketball, football, or baseball game that has a 12-game season. Your monthly P&amp;L evaluates each game and your annual P&amp;L evaluates the season. The Profit and Loss is your way to have accountability to the results you want to achieve in your season, or year.</p>\r\n<p>The word &quot;accountability&quot; often strikes fear in the hearts of small business owners. But it need not do that. Accountability, at its core, is the simple act of taking account of where you are in any given moment and then making plans, corrections, and commitments. You may see that you need to do more of something, less of something, stop something, or start something. Without a clear statement of the facts, it''s nearly impossible to take effective action and make necessary course corrections.</p>\r\n<p>This week, talk to a coach, mentor, accountant or someone who can provide support for you on your P&amp;L. Ask them to rate your P&amp;L from zero to five. Five means your P&amp;L contains high quality information--that is accurate and detailed. Three means that you are getting a rough picture of your business, but it''s not totally accurate and has insufficient detail. Zero means that your P&amp;L is only a gleam in your accountant''s eye.</p>\r\n<p>Getting in relationship with your P&amp;L means you are one step closer to a winning season!</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-05-27', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(62, 'Sales is Service', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;Everybody can be great... because anybody can serve. You don''t have to have a college degree to serve. You don''t have to make your subject and verb agree to serve. You only need a heart full of grace. A soul generated by love.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center"><em>-- Martin Luther King, Jr.</em></p>\r\n<p>Being an entrepreneur means learning to sell. Whether your company can afford to hire a sales team or you are a one-person operation, the buck stops with you.</p>\r\n<p>But if you''re like many entrepreneurs, you may resist this role even though it is one of the most critical aspects of running your business. Why? Maybe your stereotype of a sales person needs a little freshening.</p>\r\n<p>Great sales people serve. Their prospects and clients are real people to them not just a potential closed deal. Truly exceptional sales leaders help people solve problems or achieve goals whether that means recommending a good dentist or selling them a service.</p>\r\n<p>This week, try an experiment. Imagine that you are taking on your new role of Director of Sales for your organization. In this new role, everyone you meet this week is someone you are meant to help in some way-perhaps in selling them a service but perhaps in some other way.</p>\r\n<p>Notice how you approach your &quot;prospects&quot; in a new way. What kind of questions will you ask? How will you spend your time with them? You may just find out that your sales role might be the most exciting aspect of your job!</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2010-04-01', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(63, 'Make Time for Marketing', 'Michelle Lanter Smith CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">You must master your time rather than becoming a slave to the constant flow of events and demands on your time.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Brian Tracy CEO and Business Coach</p>\r\n<p>Day-to-day business operations can get in the way of planning for your business growth. These days, even though money might be tight, your marketing efforts can''t be ignored. But, minus a stern task master standing over your shoulders on a daily basis, your time is going to be monopolized by customer service, proposals, inventory management, employee issues, and on and on.</p>\r\n<p>To avoid this fatal trap, identify a person that will hold you accountable regarding the marketing of your business. Maybe she''s a trusted employee or contractor that works for you, maybe he''s a spouse, or maybe she''s a friend or business advisor. Ask this person to play this role for you and then tell him your first deadline . . . the due date on your marketing plan. And, be willing to serve as this person''s advisor in return.</p>\r\n<p>Next, go into your calendar and block off two hours per week to work on your marketing plan. Tell your advisor that you''ve done this so he can occasionally inquire as to your progress.</p>\r\n<p>In the mean time, use some of these ideas to win back those two hours per week that you just designated to building your marketing plan.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li><em>Cut the busy-work.</em>Â Stop spending hours working but not really getting anything done. Focus every day on your most important tasks. Do them first. Plan out your activities a week at a time and then prioritize them and try to assign them to a day of the week when you can get them done.</li>\r\n  <li><em>Consolidate your activities when possible.</em>Â Don''t head out every time you need something but try to consolidate business errand-running into a once a week activity.</li>\r\n  <li><em>Avoid interruptions.</em>Â Schedule time in your day for answering and make phone calls and checking voice mail. The same goes for email. Assign the first 30 minutes of the day to reviewing emails and making calls. Go back into email mid-morning and then again early afternoon and for 30 minutes before you leave for the day.</li>\r\n  <li><em>Think positive.</em>Â Recognize when you are obsessively worrying. Stop yourself and consciously change the direction of your thoughts to positive, proactive steps to address the things that worry you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>By setting time aside weekly to work on your marketing plan, and by making yourself accountable to an individual who expects to see your plan, you have a much better chance of getting your marketing efforts off the ground. And, a much better chance of seeing growth in your business.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-02-08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(64, 'To Borrow or not to Borrow?', 'Rich Lyons, Finance Coach Lyons Consulting Adjunct Instructor, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">What he needs is some way to pay back. Not some way to borrow more.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Will Rogers</p>\r\n<p>Small business owners face this question often-do I borrow money or not? When do I borrow money and what for?</p>\r\n<p>The main problem with borrowing is that you need to pay it back and still make enough to live. I just helped a retail store owner cut her entire staff. She had borrowed a great deal of money over time to pay for employees who were not justifying their own salaries. With the cutback she is now selling directly and is delighting in making money both to liveÂ <em>and</em>Â to pay back the massive debt she had acquired.</p>\r\n<p>Borrowing money may be important at certain times for your business. But before you borrow, ask yourself this: Am I maxing out my sales and delivery effort? Am I selling and delivering full time? If not, borrowing money may be premature. You need to fully use your main asset, your time, before you look for additional resources. You may need to borrow to keep hearth and home together while you sell and build your business, but it is a good rule of thumb to keep borrowing at a minimum and sales activity at a maximum.</p>\r\n<p>This week, do a personal inventory of your own resources - rate yourself on a scale of 1 to 10 (1 = you are not leveraging your own time and resources for sales and delivery; 10 = you are fully maxed in your sales and delivery efforts). Take one step towards better leveraging yourself into your business and think through if your borrowing is a help or hindrance to your long-term growth.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-04-15', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(65, 'Channel your Energy: Target your Marketing', 'Michelle Lanter Smith CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions, Inc.', '<p align="center">The customer determines at the end of the day who is successful and for what reason. Gerry Harvey, Australian CEO</p>\r\n<p>Do you know the phrase &quot;the world is your oyster?&quot; It''s a familiar phrase but not very useful when it comes to marketing your business. In fact, most of the buyers out there are not potential customers for you. Surprised? Don''t be. Marketing is not about selling to everyone. It''s about marketing to a select group of buyers that fit nicely with value that your products and services offer.</p>\r\n<p>The first step in targeting is to separate customers who make up large, general markets into smaller groupings based on selected characteristics shared by those in the group.; The next step is to hone in on the characteristics that make the groups unique. Creating a profile or a set of characteristics that specifically describes your audience can be very useful when you''re determining which marketing mediums to use (i.e., magazines, direct mail, trade shows) and what kinds of features/benefits you need to highlight in your marketing material.</p>\r\n<p><em>How do you get started in finding your target audiences?Â </em>This week, pay attention to each of the customers you encounter. Write down 3 to 5 characteristics on each one. Are they price sensitive? Do they demand above and beyond service? Are they of a certain size or are they of a certain household income? As the week comes to a close, see if you can spot a pattern. Are there some groups or segments that are emerging?See if you can identify 3 to 5 different groups of customers that consume your product or service that reside within the overall general market. At the end of the exercise ask yourself:Â <em>which segments fit the nature of my product and service offerings the best?</em>Â <em>Which segments tend to drive higher profitability for me?</em></p>\r\n<p>By focusing your marketing energies the most on customer segments that need what you can deliver (i.e., your unique value proposition), you can convert more prospects to customers using less energy and driving higher profitability.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-04-22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(66, 'Who do you know?', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Leadership Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;The way of the world is meeting people through other people.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center"><em>--Robert Kerrigan</em></p>\r\n<p>Being a successful small business owner means creating a strong network for sales and sales referrals. But where do you start?</p>\r\n<p>Believe it or not, you already know the people you need to know in order to start selling and launch your business.</p>\r\n<p>If you don''t believe it, try this simple exercise. Pick a list of five potential clients or people you would like to meet. Now take one of them and ask yourself who in your network would be able to get you closest to that person.</p>\r\n<p>(Hint: You won''t really know who can get you closest to that person until you start asking people in your network to find out who might know them or know someone they know.)</p>\r\n<p>Chances are very good that you are no more than two or three degrees of separation from almost any person you would like to meet.</p>\r\n<p>At one of my networking workshops, I mentioned that I wanted to meet the CEO of Boeing. As it turned out, someone in the room had a brother who was good friends with him and I was able to invite him to an event I was hosting.</p>\r\n<p>This week reach out to your network to help you meet the person you want to meet. The person who connects you may come as a surprise, it may not even be someone you thought of as a business relationship. But if you start thinking creatively, you''ll be amazed at the possibilities that exist in your current network.</p>\r\n<p><em>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation. Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</em></p>', '', '', '2010-04-29', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(67, 'Free Marketing: Just what the doctor ordered', 'Michelle Lanter Smith CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">Growth demands a temporary surrender of security</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Gail Sheehy</p>\r\n<p>Nowadays everyone one is looking to get their word out without spending a fortune. Who blames them, times are tough. But when the economy is rough, it''s time to invest in marketing, not pull back. Studies show that companies that increase their marketing efforts during tough economic times, do better over the long-run than companies that cut back.</p>\r\n<p>But instead of talking about investing more money, let''s talk about investing more time. After all, if sales are down, you should have more time available to market your business.</p>\r\n<p>Social media is quickly becoming an effective way to dialogue with potential customers. And guess what? It''s not expensive and it''s a great small business tool! In fact, reports show that this is one area where small business is ahead of the big guys.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So, what exactly is Social Media?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Here''s what Wikipedia says (a great social media tool by the way).Â <strong>Social media</strong>Â is Internet-based tools for sharing and discussing information among human beings. The term most often refers to activities that integrate technology, social interaction, and the construction of words, pictures, videos and audio. This interaction, and the manner in which information is presented, depends on the varied perspectives and &quot;building&quot; of shared meaning among communities, as people share their stories and experiences.</p>\r\n<p>Some of the most common social-networking sites that you''ve probably heard of are Facebook, eBay, and YouTube. About one in three adults visits each of these sites.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Social Media-we''re talking main stream now</strong></p>\r\n<p>More than two-thirds (68 percent) of online Americans say they visit online blogs, communities, or social networks. One-third engage in product research online to help make purchase decisions. Furthermore, the frequency of social media visits also is on the rise, with 42% of adults saying they visit these sites more now than they did six months ago. 1</p>\r\n<p><strong>Think it''s only for young people? Think again.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Today, social media is created and consumed by millions of people worldwide from virtually every socio-economic background. In the first quarter of this year, the number of people over age using Facebook doubled. The majority of Facebook users are now over 25.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So why invest your time in social media initiatives?</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>Drive High Quality Traffic to Your Website</li>\r\n  <p>Depending on your industry, social media and networking sites can send quality traffic to your site. Some companies are using YouTube to attract and drive traffic to their website. Cysco decided to reach their mostly male, professional audience using humor when launching a new router. Besides buildingÂ <em>uber-user</em>Â website, they posted theirÂ <em>uber-user</em>Â videos on You Tube (for free), probably making it one of their most successful launches yet.</p>\r\n  <p>A good strategy is to select sites that are somehow specific to your industry and then let the creative juices flow. Just as millions of people are using search engines every day, millions of people are now using social media and networking sites as well.</p>\r\n  <li>Links to Your Website</li>\r\n  <p>Websites essentially need three things if they are to experience good visibility in the search engines - 1) good content 2) good SEO and 3) good links. There are two ways to get links from other sites: naturally or pay for them. Buying links of course is easier, but due to Google''s recent war on paid links, they may not bear fruit. So, natural links are better.</p>\r\n  <p>One way to obtain natural links is to link back to your original web site within the social media sites you set up. Many social media sites will allow you to include a blurb about yourself and your company and add links back to your site. Once you get your social media profiles indexed, they will count as inbound links to your main web site. So bottom line, the social media profiles you set up create opportunities for natural links back to your site. Best of all, they'';re free!</p>\r\n  <li>Branding</li>\r\n  <p>With social media sites popping up everywhere, it''s important to incorporate them into the branding of your company or product. By developing good content that features your brand, you will become the expert in the eyes of your potential customers. This is especially true on sites where people come to you for your advice and knowledge (i.e., blogs or microblogs like twitter). As people read your chatter, a trust will begin and they will become more familiar with your brand and more likely to buy your products. Facebook and MySpace are also a great for this and can help you build an online community that you can easily send news out to such as, special offers, coupons, upcoming events.</p>\r\n  <li>Customer feedback</li>\r\n  <p>Social media is used by many consumers as a way to easily conduct research on products they wish to purchase. In fact, affluent visitors ($75k or greater in annual income) are most likely to research products online before buying (43%). This may come as a surprise to many of you non-believers, but Baby Boomers visitors are significantly more likely than other groups to read or post comments about products and services on these sites (37%).</p>\r\n  <p>Forty-seven percent of all respondents say that blogs, communities, and social networks have influenced their decision to purchase particular brands or services to at least some extent.</p>\r\n  <p>Insight into what drives consumers to buy, how to tailor content to different target groups, and even how to better engage with targeted buyers in these influential online forums, will all have a significant impact on the competitiveness of a todayâ€™s small business.</p>\r\n  <li>Go Find Your Customer</li>\r\n  <p>Blogging is an easy way for a business to more easily go meet their target audience where they begin most online searches that lead to their website-Google. A lot of website traffic originates on Google, so it only makes sense to continue efforts to get better placement in the search results. Blogging on your site is a very solid way to optimize content for search engines-especially if you''re updating often and using the right methods.</p>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Get started now. Social Media works. Here''s 6 Must Do''s.</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>Start a blog. Try Wordpress.com.Â <em>It''s free!</em></li>\r\n  <li>Comment on other blogs.Â <em>That''s free too!</em></li>\r\n  <li>Get active on Yahoo Answers.Â <em>Yep. Free.</em></li>\r\n  <li>Make and share videos on YouTube.Â <em>Ask your kids. It''s free.</em></li>\r\n  <li>Create a Facebook or MySpace Page.Â <em>Of course it''s free.</em></li>\r\n  <li>Participate in LinkedIn.Â <em>Professionals have now caught on too--you guessed it-it''s free.</em></li>\r\n  <p><em>1Statistics sourced in this article are from MarketTools, Market Charts August/September issue. MarketTools Insight Reports are regular reports of findings on topical, national issues of interest. Data is based on feedback from 1,000 online US respondents age 18+, drawn from ZoomPanel, MarketTools'' proprietary online sample source.</em></p>\r\n</ol>', '', '', '2009-11-03', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(68, 'How to Elminate the Worms in Your Marketing Efforts', 'Michelle Lanter Smith CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing &Sales Solutions, Inc.', '<p align="center">Judge each day not by its harvest but by the seeds you plant.</p>\r\n<p align="center">-Anonymous</p>\r\n<p>Often times for many small businesses, lead generation just really amounts to &quot;picking the low hanging fruit.&quot; We send a post card or make some cold calls, hoping that we find a few healthy ones ready to be picked and ready to buy now. Otherwise, who knows what will become of them in the deep recesses of a file drawer or forgotten database?</p>\r\n<p>To me, that''s not marketing-it''s soliciting.Marketing takes a look at theÂ <em>whole</em>Â buying process. You must tend to the fruit through the whole growing season . . . from bud to harvest. A good farmer knows that if he does nothing to care for his crop during the growing season and finally pays a visit to his orchard at harvest time to pick his apples, he discovers that there are few healthy fruit and a lot of bad apples filled with worms and disease.</p>\r\n<p>Same goes with marketing. You must tend to theÂ <em>whole buying process.</em>Â From the customer''s<em>awareness</em>Â that there is an issue, to hisÂ <em>interest</em>Â in investigating various solutions, to hisÂ <em>desire</em>Â to fix the issue, and finally toÂ <em>action</em>Â . . . where he engages or purchases the solution that will solve his problem. This is theÂ <em>AIDA Model</em>Â (Awareness - Interest - Desire-Action). It is the foundational structure that should be utilized when creating a successful marketing program.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So how do you make the AIDA model work for you?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Awareness</p>\r\n<p>In theÂ <em>awareness stage</em>, a buyer becomes aware that there is a possible solution to his nagging problem. Instead of ignoring or tuning out the marketing message, he begins to tune in. Some buyers remain in the awareness stage for a length of time, while others move quickly to the interest stage.</p>\r\n<p><em>Some potential marketing tactics to consider for the Awareness stage . . .</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Associations &amp; Trade Magazines alignment by joining and participating</li>\r\n  <li>PR through published articles</li>\r\n  <li>Speaking engagements for yourself and your company experts</li>\r\n  <li>&quot;Brand-building&quot; advertising in media that your target audience reads</li>\r\n  <li>Social media-blogging, RSS feeds, Facebook</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Interest</p>\r\n<p>During theÂ <em>interest</em>Â stage a buyer investigates various solutions or providers. He''s reading articles, surfing the Internet, attending helpful seminars or conferences. The goal here is to provide the prospect withÂ <strong>information and knowledge.</strong>Â This is why good content is key on your web site or in your marketing collateral.</p>\r\n<p>This is also where brand awareness at the individual level is built, as prospects begin to see your brand throughout the various mediums. An advertising piece as well as direct mail/e-mail will be more apt to get his attention in this stage.</p>\r\n<p><em>Marketing tactics in the Interest stage include . . .</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Events/Webinars/Podcasts</li>\r\n  <li>PR -; articles and news announcements</li>\r\n  <li>Advertising - both in print and online</li>\r\n  <li>Direct Mail with &quot;call to actions that will provide more information to the prospect&quot;</li>\r\n  <li>Internet through SEO, pay per click, newsletters and blasts</li>\r\n  <li>Inside Sales - should be nurturing and informative</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Desire</p>\r\n<p>In theÂ <em>desire stage</em>, the buyer is ready to do something tangible to move further in the process. He may ready to share information to a potential supplier so he can get an accurate quote. Or, if he''s further down the path, he may want a demo or a sample to help him evaluate the solution provider. Once again, brand awareness is critical for your solution to be selected as a possible candidate.</p>\r\n<p><em>Here are the marketing tactics you''ll want in place . . .</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Direct Mail</li>\r\n  <li>Internet</li>\r\n  <li>Interactive assessments</li>\r\n  <li>Request for quotes</li>\r\n  <li>Case Studies &amp; References available</li>\r\n  <li>Inside Sales - knowledgeable and responsive</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Action</p>\r\n<p>In theÂ <em>action phase</em>, a buyer is just about ready to make his decision. Before doing so, he may check references and talk to key influencers. Once again, not only your sample &amp; quote comes into play, but also the word-of-mouth element. An established brand identity and good reputation within the industry and with industry associations will give you the edge.</p>\r\n<p><em>There are two types of marketing tactics that come into play here:</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>Brand Building Tactics</li>\r\n  <li>Experience Tactics such as customer service</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Obviously, I''ve mentioned a plethora of marketing tactics. An effective campaign doesn''t have to use them all, just the right ones. Your challenge is to select the appropriate marketing mix that appeals to your target audience, who is in various stages of AIDA.</p>', '', '', '2009-11-10', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(69, 'Sales Success . . . How do you view yourself? ', 'Roula Crews President, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">Self-confidence is the first requisite to great undertakings.</p>\r\n<p align="center">Samuel Johnson</p>\r\n<p>Whether you''re getting ready to make that first call to a prospective customer or going in to close the sale, your likelihood of success is much greater if you approach the customer and the task with self-confidence. How you view yourself can make all the difference.</p>\r\n<p>Successful salespeople understand the importance of educating themselves in two areas: their prospects and their own products and services. But there''s another leg to this &quot;Being-prepared-for-the-sale&quot; tripod, a critical one, indeed. It''s preparing your mindset.</p>\r\n<p>Do you view yourself as a successful salesperson? Or as a salesperson who''s a nuisance and interrupts someone''s day when you call them. Do you hesitate prior to picking up the phone, concerned that you''ll be bothering the person on the other end? That attitude is a recipe for sales disaster.</p>\r\n<p>Many salespeople get nervous before making an important sales presentation. But their real fears are fear of failure and fear of being rejected. While failure itself is real, the fear of it is a condition of the mind. It is said, &quot;You become what you think.&quot; If that''s the case, then everyone in sales should be thinking &quot;SUCCESS!&quot; Compare &quot;I failed&quot; to &quot;I just learned what never to do again&quot; and you see that it''s a completely different mindset. It''s the path of success, not failure!</p>\r\n<p>Believing in what you do is critical to projecting the attitude that encourages prospects rather than driving them away. Succeeding in sales requires that you understand and appreciate your role as a valuable resource for the person on the other end. Your product may be just what your prospect has been seeking for months. The service you offer may provide an opportunity for your client to turn around his company in a way he didn''t know was possible.</p>\r\n<p>I challenge you to think about your own sales approach:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Belief drives confidence</strong>. Believe that you can achieve whatever you set as your sales goal. You must believe that you work for the greatest company and provide the best products and services</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Belief drives passion</strong>Â Passion exhibited by the salesperson creates a desire to buy in the heart and mind of the prospect. Passion exhibited by the salesperson converts selling to buying.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>My strategy is to become a valuable resource for my clients so that they will benefit, come to respect me, and then call me wanting to purchase my products and services. This success stems from an &quot;I Can Attitude&quot; not an &quot;I think I Can.&quot;</p>\r\n<p>Here''s to Successful Selling!</p>', '', '', '2009-11-17', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(70, 'The Golden Egg: Let Your Customers Hatch More Sales for You ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith, Marketing Coach CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions, Inc', '<p align="center">Revolve your world around the customer and more customers will revolve around you.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Heather Williams</p>\r\n<p>So often, clients tell me &quot;I need to increase my sales . . . help me find new customers.&quot; And my response is:Â <em>What have you done to get more out of your existing customers?</em></p>\r\n<p>Retaining and growing your existing customer base (or simply put, getting repeat business) is usually the fastest and easiest way to grow your revenue; unfortunately, it is also the most overlooked. A customer retention program can be a powerful tool in the arsenal of customer relationship management. Retention is important to most companies because the cost of acquiring a new customer is far greater than the cost of maintaining a relationship with a current customer.</p>\r\n<p>I like to call a company''s customer base The Golden Egg. If it''s watched over and kept warm, it''s worth its weight in gold, paying out dividends in the form of increased revenue (and profitability). Here''s why you need to focus on retention:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li><strong>Don''t let your competitor steal The Golden Goose.</strong>Â That''s means, use retention marketing efforts to keep your profitable customers. For many firms, customer profitability is skewed in such a way that losing the most profitable customers has a very serious effect. In many banks, for example, the top 30 percent of customers, when ranked by profitability, can make up 100-150 percent of total customer profitability. That''s right--the bottom eighty percent of customers may provide no profitability or, worse yet, destroy 50 percent</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Build customer knowledge.</strong>Â In addition to saving profitable customers, retention programs allow companies to collect data about their customers. All you have to do is ASK, and most customers are happy to respond. This data can be used to better understand, target, market to, and communicate with customers or to customize future interactions with customers.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Uncover ways to improve satisfaction.</strong>Through your marketing, you can solicit feedback from your clients. Although most people think of marketing as some form of direct solicitation for a service, the marketing itself can actually focus on improving client satisfaction through vehicles such as surveys. When you survey clients, you are communicating to them that you want to be as good as you can be. This is great branding for you, and the feedback you get can be invaluable to improve your services across the board and to fix satisfaction issues with current clients.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Keep mindshare (and wallet-share) high.Â </strong>With your current clients, you can be sure of two things:\r\n    <ol>\r\n      <li>If you''re not in front of your clients, they''re not thinking about you-they''re focusing on the challenges of the day.</li>\r\n      <li>Your competitors are trying to get your clients to switch from you to them. To make sure your clients continue to think about you, keep your messages in front of them when you, physically, are not.</li>\r\n    </ol>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li><strong>Generate leads for new services.Â </strong>If you have multiple services or products you want your clients to purchase, one of the best ways to let clients know about them is to tell them, over and over, through marketing. The most likely buyers of new services are satisfied buyers of current services.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Meet their friends.</strong>Â One of the best ways to find new customers is through existing customers. Make it a habit to ask your clients if they know of anyone that could also use your product or service. And don''t wait until your relationship has aged, ask them early-on . . . even before they''ve bought from you. There''s nothing wrong with letting people know that your firm is compensated in two ways: money and referrals.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Bottom Line: retention programs can be a relatively inexpensive means of making customers feel special, increase their purchases and recommend prospects.</p>', '', '', '2009-10-06', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(71, 'Get the Most from Your Customers ', 'Teri Latter Marketing Program Manager, Hi-Impact Marketing', '<p align="center">What is research but a blind date with knowledge?</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Will Henry</p>\r\n<p>Market research is an effective way to determine what the attributes of your product line should be and who are likely to be your customers. Sometimes, however, time or budget constraints preclude the use of market research. Fortunately, if you already have customers, then you have the means to do on-going research right at your fingertips.</p>\r\n<p>Your current customers are a wealth of information when it comes to your products and your service . . . all you have to do is ask! Here are some must-ask questions:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Find out how your customers first heard of you.Â </strong>This will help you evaluate the effectiveness of your different marketing tactics. Ask prospective customers this question, too.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>After the sale, follow-up.</strong>Â Find out how the customer felt about the buying experience and how they like the product or service they received from you. If they love something you are doing it, make sure to share the good news with others in the company-and keep on doing it!</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Be sure to ask what they don''t like about your product, the customer service experience or the sales process your company uses.</strong>Â No one likes to hear bad feedback, but hearing directly from your customers about where your company is falling short is some of the best information you can receive . . . if you choose to do something about it.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Find out what else they would like from your company.Â </strong>Some of the best ideas for a new product or service come directly from customers. They''re the ones who are out there using your product regularly and know best what they need-listen to them!</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Ask your customer for contacts they know who might be interested in your product.Â </strong>You never know who they might know and a referral from a happy customer makes the sales job a little easier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Now that you know what to ask, what are some vehicles for getting their insights? Consider the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Make your post-sale phone call multi-purpose.</strong>Â Of course, a follow-up call is a great way to hear how your customer is enjoying your product. The call also begins to establish an on-going relationship with the customer; after all, you want your customers to be repeat customers.If the customer is satisfied with your product, this would be a good time to ask for referrals. If he''s not, here''s your opportunity to correct the situation.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Use email as a great way to keep in touch with customers and get their thoughts about new products.</strong>Â Send a short email asking how they are enjoying your product or soliciting ideas for changes to your products.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>How about blogging?Â </strong>Make your website interactive by starting a blog. A blog gives you a way to pose questions to customers visiting your website; your customers can respond right there on your site.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Throw a customer appreciation party.</strong>Â Bring your customers together at your location and spend time getting their feedback on your products and services. Make it fun, show them you appreciate their loyalty and they''ll be glad to share their thoughts with you.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Make the most of that valuable asset you already possess-your customers. You''ll be glad you did!</p>', '', '', '2009-10-13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(72, 'Objections: A Gateway to Your Prospect''s Thought Process ', 'Roula Crews President, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">I like to think of sales as the ability to gracefully persuade, not manipulate, a person or persons into a win-win situation.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Bo Bennett</p>\r\n<p>Learning to overcome objections effectively starts with a change in attitude. It is natural to feel defensive when encountering objections. So often we think:</p>\r\n<p>Do you doubt me? Do you doubt my product? Do you doubt my company? What if you ask me a question I can''t answer?</p>\r\n<p>Objections are not necessarily a bad thing. They can reveal a lot to the salesperson about the prospect''s train of thought and point of reference. They also open up the dialogue on a more even playing field because you know more about the issues you have to deal with to get the sale.</p>\r\n<p>Here are some things to remember when you are faced with customer resistance:</p>\r\n<p>Prospects have objections because:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>They need to get a different view of the situation</li>\r\n  <li>They need details to make the right buying decision</li>\r\n  <li>They want to understand the value/revenue/benefit they can receive from your product</li>\r\n  <li>They would like more information to evaluate the product</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Objections reveal:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>A gateway to your customer''s thought process</li>\r\n  <li>The customer''s primary needs or areas of interest</li>\r\n  <li>Buying motives of the customer in making the buying decision</li>\r\n  <li>Your role as the salesperson in handling the objection is to:</li>\r\n  <li>Be the product expert and act like it</li>\r\n  <li>Inform your customer as to how this product will solve their problem</li>\r\n  <li>Build a sense of value so the customer will want the product</li>\r\n  <li>Listen and help your customer &quot;bridge the gap&quot; between hesitating and making a move to buy</li>\r\n  <li>Not get defensive, you will lose your power</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Bottom line: use objections to your advantage. Show the prospect that you really hear his concerns or issues, then provide a direct answer to the objection if you are able to-don''t bluff your way through it. Once you feel you''ve addressed the objection, be sure to ask your prospect if he feels the objection has been addressed. Now, you''re ready to ask for the order; you''ve earned it.</p>', '', '', '2009-10-20', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(73, 'Is It a Warm Prospect or a Cold Lead? ', 'Roula Crews President, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions', '<p align="center">I never learn anything by talking. I only learn things when I ask questions.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~Lou Holtz</p>\r\n<p>You have a list of targeted leads and now it''s up to you to determine which companies on the list are prospects. One of the best ways to accomplish this task is through the use of effective open-ended questions, the answers to which will allow you to determine if a given company represents an opportunity for your company . . . . or not.</p>\r\n<p>The questions that work best in helping you uncover the lead''s potential will vary depending upon the business you are in, but there are certain questions that will help you get started no matter what. Here are some that I find to be great for getting the dialogue going:</p>\r\n<p><strong>For Establishing Rapport, Trust and Credibility</strong></p>\r\n<p>Tell me a little about your company and its history -<em>I know, it''s not a question, but it gets them talking!</em></p>\r\n<p>What kind of challenges are you facing?</p>\r\n<p>What''s the most important priority to you with this and why?</p>\r\n<p>What other issues are important to you?</p>\r\n<p>What would you like to see improved? How do you measure that?</p>\r\n<p><strong>For Information Gathering</strong></p>\r\n<p>What prompted you/your company to look into this situation?</p>\r\n<p>What are your expectations/requirements for this product/service?</p>\r\n<p>What is it that you would like to see accomplished?</p>\r\n<p>Who have worked with in the past? How satisfied were you with their product/service?</p>\r\n<p>What is your current process?</p>\r\n<p>What challenge does that process create?</p>\r\n<p>What are the best things about that process?</p>\r\n<p><strong>For Understanding the Impact of Your Solution</strong></p>\r\n<p>If you could overcome these challenges, what would happen to your company''s financial situation?</p>\r\n<p>How would implementing these changes affect your ability to compete?</p>\r\n<p>How do you think senior management would evaluate the success of this initiative?</p>\r\n<p>If you don''t solve this particular challenge, what kind of difficulties will you face going forward?</p>\r\n<p><strong>For Qualifying and Determining Next Steps</strong></p>\r\n<p>What is your timeline for implementing/purchasing this type of service/product?</p>\r\n<p>What budget has been established for this?</p>\r\n<p>What questions do you have?</p>\r\n<p>Who else is involved in this decision?</p>\r\n<p>What do you see as the next action steps?</p>\r\n<p>Using these questions should get the information flow going and help you determine if you''ve got a warm prospect or a dead-end lead.</p>', '', '', '2009-10-27', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(74, 'E-mail Marketing--Building Your In-house List ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith CEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions, Inc.', '<p align="center">We can build upon foundations anywhere if they are well and truly laid.</p>\r\n<p align="center">Ivy Compton-Burnett</p>\r\n<p>Electronic newsletters, tips, and magazines (e-zines) are all very powerful marketing tools but, without people to send them to, they provide absolutely no value. Renting e-mail lists can be ill-advised and often forbidden by e-mail marketing providers, costing significant dollars with questionable return. Building an in-house list is your best bet.</p>\r\n<p>Implementing these steps can help you motivate your web site visitors to &quot;opt-in&quot; and become subscribers:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Offer visitors free and valuable information if they subscribe. The offer could be a free white paper or e-book.&amp; But make sure that the offer is relevant to your business and easy to deliver.</li>\r\n  <li>Host a subscription contest wherein everyone who subscribes will be automatically entered in a drawing to win fabulous prizes.</li>\r\n  <li>Give away something for free that you normally would charge for, such as free delivery, extended warranty, etc.</li>\r\n  <li>Provide a free sample of your electronic publication online so visitors can benefit from the information right away and motivate them to subscribe.</li>\r\n  <li>Place a dollar figure on your electronic publication and then motivate people to join by offering it for free for a limited time.</li>\r\n  <li>Ask current subscribers to enlist their friends and families to join and offer them an incentive for doing so.</li>\r\n  <li>Publish positive reviews and testimonials about your e-zine on your web site to motivate visitors to subscribe.</li>\r\n  <li>Offer a discount on all products and services you sell to people who subscribe to your e-newsletter. You can make up the lost revenue by increasing your overall sales volumes.</li>\r\n  <li>Create a members-only section in your web site and offer free and exclusive access only to people who subscribe to your e-zine. Increase the perceived value of your members-only sections by including information, discounts, and other special offers to which only members can gain access.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>If you already have an e-newsletter, this week select one of these ideas and begin developing it so that you can implement it within the next 2-3 weeks. If you don''t, spend some time evaluating whether this great tool can work for you.</p>', '', '', '2009-09-01', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(75, 'Generating Value ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">Price is what you pay. Value is what you get.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Warren Buffett</p>\r\n<p>As a small business owner, it is important to keep in mind the perspective of your customers. On one of our last teleconferences together, we discussed the Dynamic Value model, which was first developed by Marshall Thurber. We encouraged you to identify the features and benefits of the products and services of your company, and then to compare them to those of your competition. Remember, it''s theÂ <em>benefits</em>, not theÂ <em>features,Â </em>that your customers will remember.</p>\r\n<p>This week, take a moment to ask a customer or two about the value that you bring to them.</p>\r\n<p>You can review the presentation on dynamic value from Teleconference #3 on the Business Accelerator website, then share your learns with me and your fellow participants on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies</a>Â blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2010-09-08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
