(76, 'A Little Dab''ll Do Ya ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">We''re Number Two. We Try Harder.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Avis Rental Car</p>\r\n<p align="center">Where''s the beef?</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Wendy''s</p>\r\n<p>We''ve all seen great advertising slogans that stick in our mind long after we first hear them. Many of us still remember Brylcream''s &quot;Little dab''ll do ya,&quot; Wendy''s &quot;Where''s the beef?&quot; and Avis'' &quot;We try harder.&quot; Others from both past and present probably stick in your mind as well.</p>\r\n<p>On our last two teleconferences we discussed building relationships with your customers and marketing. We talked about the value of a good elevator speech, bumper sticker, and slogan in getting your message across quickly so that your potential customer wants to learn more.</p>\r\n<p>Have you developed and used your bumper sticker or slogan?</p>\r\n<p>If not, this week, continue to work on your elevator speeches and bumper stickers. Try them out on your friends and business associates. Ask for feedback from your prospects and customers - find out what they think about whether what you''ve developed captures the core of your business . . . and their interest.</p>\r\n<p>Share your thoughts and experiences with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies</a>Â blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-09-15', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(77, 'Roman Accountability ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">The ancient Romans had a tradition: whenever one of their engineers constructed an arch, as the capstone was hoisted into place, the engineer assumed accountability for his work in the most profound way possible: he stood under the arch.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Michael Armstrong</p>\r\n<p>In last week''s Teleconference, we discussed setting up and maintaining systems of accountability in your business. The overall aim of all of these methods is to help you to build your business in a way that is effective and sustainable - in other words, to build an arch you feel confident standing under. If you do not feel good about the strength of your business yourself, chances are your customers won''t either - especially in the long-run. Nor will banks or other potential investors.</p>\r\n<p>This week, continue to work on identifying the critical systems you need to operate your business effectively - and the measurements you need to have in place to see whether or not they are working. Create a dashboard for yourself to help you monitor progress in one of your chosen systems. Ask your allies and business colleagues to look at them with you and give you advice on whether you''ve picked the best things to pay attention to and what they see in the data you have gathered. Share your thoughts and experiences with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies</a>Â blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-09-22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(78, 'Six Steps to Better Direct Mail', 'Teri Latter, Marketing Program Manager Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions, Inc.', '<p align="center">Before anything else, preparation is the key to success.</p>\r\n<p align="center">--Alexander Graham Bell</p>\r\n<p>Direct mail is not inexpensive, but sometimes it''s simply the best way to get the word out. Now, more than ever, making sure it is effective becomes a top priority. Before you even get to the writing and design of your postcard or letter or email, there''s some homework you need to do to boost the likelihood of success of your campaign:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>Know your audience.Â </strong>While the Direct Marketing Association indicates that the average response rate to direct mail is now 2.61%, the use of a well-targeted list can drive that number up to 5% or higher. It''s worth your time to determine exactly who your target market is and mail just to them.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Know yourself.Â </strong>You should understand the value you bring to your customers how do they benefit by buying from you instead of from your competitor. Make sure you know what it is that separates you from your competitors. These are the things a copywriter is going to need to develop strong copy.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>What do you want?Â </strong>Spend time determining what your goal is for your direct marketing campaign. Is it to develop awareness of your company in the marketplace? Or, are you trying to generate leads? This, too, will figure into the copywriting effort.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Develop a compelling offer.</strong>Â Regardless of the goal of your campaign, you want the recipients to take some kind of action. By knowing what it is that makes your target audience tick, you can determine what it is that''s going to make them respond to your direct mail piece-is it a free sample? Or a DVD about how your product will increase their sales? Maybe a discount on their first purchase? Whatever it is, it has to be tantalizing enough for them to take action.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Start small.</strong>Â Sure, there might be 3000 companies you want to contact, but if your campaign doesn''t resonate with that target, you''re going to have wasted a lot of money to get few responses. Instead, test the waters by sending to 250 or even fewer. If the response rate meets or exceeds your expectations, send out the next wave. If it doesn''t, consider tweaking the offer or re-working the copy before sending out more.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Once is not enough.</strong>Â Keep in mind that sending out to the same target multiple times can increase the overall success of a campaign. Consider using a smaller list of prospects to which you''ll send multiple pieces. Mix it up a little, too, by starting with a letter, following up with a postcard and even a phone call.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>We all want to use our marketing budget wisely. Invest time in properly preparing for your direct mail campaign and the return on your dollar investment will show it.</p>', '', '', '2009-09-29', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(79, 'Adding Fuel to The Sales Fire ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">Goals are the fuel in the furnace of achievement.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Brian Tracy</p>\r\n<p>Having clear behavioral and dollar goals adds fuel to the fire of your sales activity. With clear goals you can achieve more, faster.</p>\r\n<p>Keep your behavioral goals mind when you set up your daily and weekly routines - when you''re putting your dial list together, setting up your tick list and activity spreadsheet, blocking out time for appointments. Use them to guide you in making minute-by-minute choices between wasting time and digging in. Use them to inspire you to thin-slice your time and squeeze in a few more calls, to ask for appointments, to try a test close, to hear a &quot;no&quot; as a maybe.</p>\r\n<p>Ask yourself: How will this thing that I''m doing right now help me to reach my goal? If I do everything on my list today, will I hit my target, will I achieve my goal? If the answer to the second question is &quot;no,&quot; then you know you need to rethink your behavioral goals to be sure they multiply to your revenue goals. Ask questions and share your learns with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies</a>Â blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-08-04', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(80, 'Selling Hope', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">In the factory we make cosmetics; in the drugstore we sell hope.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Charles Revson</p>\r\n<p>Many sales professionals make the mistake of getting caught up in trying to sell the features and dimensions of their product first -; rather than engaging with the customer around their hopes and dreams, about what they hope to accomplish.</p>\r\n<p>Revlon Cosmetics produces colorful powders, liquids, gels, and fragrances. The founder of the company, Charles Revson realized that the reason people bought his products, however, was hope - perhaps hope for a more glamorous, youthful, healthful appearance. Imagine what it would be like if a sales clerk at the cosmetics counter approached customers with the opener: &quot;Let me tell you about zinc sterate.&quot;</p>\r\n<p>This is not to say that the ingredients or components of the product or service aren''t important - or that customers won''t consider them in their buying decisions. But it''s important to understand the bigger picture in positioning yourself with a client and in the marketplace. Are you selling floor wax - or are you selling a more beautiful and welcoming home? Are you selling IT systems - or are you selling straight-forward solutions to vexing problems that keep companies from delighting their customers with high quality service?</p>\r\n<p>What do you really sell? Work with your allies and business associates to create a statement similar to Revson''s - and use that to develop and refine your sales approach. Share your thoughts and experiences with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies</a>Â blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-08-11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(81, 'Customers as Guests ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">We see our customers as invited guests to a party, and we are the hosts.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Jeff Bezos, Amazon</p>\r\n<p>Learning to build strong rapport with your customers is essential. Treating them as your guests rather than as impositions or problems to manage will go a long way toward building more successful relationships. After all, they are the reason you are in business.</p>\r\n<p>Building productive business relationships requires you to listen to your customers and understand their perspective and needs. You need to know when to talk and when to remain silent. How to build trust and how to seal a deal. How to articulate the value of what you have to offer. All of these are skills that anyone can learn with practice and self-awareness.</p>\r\n<p>At the heart of the matter, though, lie your beliefs about your customers, their views, and their role in your business. Mahatma Ghandi insisted: &quot;We are not doing [the customer] a favor by serving him. He is doing us a favor by giving us an opportunity to do so.&quot;</p>\r\n<p>How do you treat your customers? As guests or impositions? Do an honest inventory of your beliefs about customers (yours and those in general) and their role in your business. Examine the negative judgments you may have about them. Maybe you think that they''re usually wrong; they''re too picky; they don''t really know what they want until you tell them; they take forever to make a decision; etc.</p>\r\n<p>Consider taking a different perspective. Customers may be &quot;wrong&quot; because you''ve made up your mind that yours is the only right way, and have closed yourself off to other perspectives that may reveal entirely new possibilities for your business. Customers may be &quot;too picky&quot; because they are concerned about the quality of what you are offering. Each judgment you have about them may reveal an opportunity for you to engage at a deeper level with them and with your business.</p>\r\n<p>Share your thoughts and experiences with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies</a>Â blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-08-18', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(82, 'Lasting Impressions ', 'Michelle Lanter SmithCEO, Hi-Impact Marketing and Sales Solutions, Inc.', '<p align="center">First impressions are the most lasting.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ 18th century English proverb</p>\r\n<p>To truly master the art of networking and to leave no &quot;opportunity for new business&quot; stone unturned then you must go beyond your traditional networking strategies and include tactics that will get you noticed. Most people in attendance at a networking event are dressed in business attire-a sea of blue and brown. But a while ago, an avid networking friend was at a local chamber of commerce of event, when in walked a man wearing a wetsuit, goggles, and a snorkel hanging from his neck. Needless to say, he stood out in the crowd and for the next hour was bombarded with questions, humorous greetings, and strange glances. A few months later, my friend and his wife decided to go on a vacation with plans for scuba diving. Guess who he called to take the required training to get PADI-certified before the trip? You got it, the man in the wet suit.</p>\r\n<p>Not all networking events are suitable for these type of unforgettable tactics, nor is every business able to produce a memorable promotional gimmick, however, you can use your dress to leave a lasting impression and stand out in the crowd.</p>\r\n<p>Another way you can make a lasting impression is by taking some time to create an interesting nametag for yourself that will get noticed, be memorable, and break the ice. In addition to stating your name, add a message that will prompt people to ask you questions, not to mention a few laughs. For example, if you''re a financial planner, instead of a nametag that says, &quot;Mike, Financial Planner&quot;, create one that says &quot;Hi my name is Mike and I can show you how to make $100,000 next year.&quot;</p>\r\n<p>Finally, maximize your time best at networking opportunities by arriving 20 minutes before the event and staying 20 minutes after it ends. If you''re real objective is to meet as many people as you can, then think of yourself as the host and greet as many people as possible before the event and see them off after the event. The majority of people won''t know the difference if you are the host or not but they will remember you as the person that welcomed and broke the ice by greeting them warmly.</p>', '', '', '2009-08-25', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(83, 'Wisely Taking Account', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">To state the facts frankly is not to despair the future nor indict the past.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ John F. Kennedy</p>\r\n<p>Judgments and defenses must be overcome to see clearly what we have and what our business is. In our first teleconference, we began by discussing the importance of taking account and keeping good numbers.</p>\r\n<p>The concept of &quot;accountability&quot; often strikes fear in the hearts of small business owners. But it need not do that. Accountability is, at its core, the simple act of taking account of where you are in any given moment and then making plans, corrections, and commitments. You may see that you need to do more of something, less of something, stop something, or start something. Without a clear statement of the facts about what is true now, it''s nearly impossible to take effective action and make necessary course corrections.</p>\r\n<p>Many of the small business owners we coach are hesitant to put systems in place that will allow them to see clearly how their business is doing and what to expect. They drag their feet on putting together a P&amp;L statement, saying that it''s just something for an accountant to do and there''s no time or money to make it happen.</p>\r\n<p>Big mistake. A P&amp;L statement lets you know the score during a particular period of time - daily, monthly, quarterly, yearly. It tells you the money you took in (revenue), the money that went out (direct and indirect costs), and what you made (gross and net profits). It is a critical tool for small business owners, and the skills related to understanding how to read and interpret a P&amp;L (and a balance sheet) are fundamental to the success of your business.</p>\r\n<p>If you do not have a P&amp;L statement or balance sheet for your business, take steps to get one in place as soon as possible. If you do have them, make sure you understand how to read and interpret them in order to make better business decisions. Don''t just leave it for your accountant to do. Review the presentation from the teleconference for other tips. Ask questions and share your learnings with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies blog on the Forum</a>Â of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-07-07', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(84, 'Pay Yourself First', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">Pay Yourself First!</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Standard Financial Advice</p>\r\n<p>You have probably heard people giving this advice when they talk about personal finances, urging you to put some money away in savings rather than just living paycheck to paycheck.</p>\r\n<p>When we offer this advice to small business owners, we mean something slightly different. As you learned in the first teleconference, a common mistake entrepreneurs make is to think that all the money you make in your business is profit. Not so.</p>\r\n<p>Even if you are a sole proprietor, your profit and loss (P&amp;L) statement should include -- in the category of Direct or Variable Costs -- a line for &quot;sales commission&quot; to represent the money you owe yourself as the business&quot; sales professional. It should also include an entry for &quot;delivery costs&quot; - representing the compensation you are owed for delivering the goods or services produced. In the Fixed Expenses, you should also include the payroll costs for the money you owe yourself as the business&quot; administrator. It is only after you have subtracted your Direct/Variable Costs and Fixed Expenses from your Revenue that you are able to calculate your Net Profit - or the money the business truly generated.</p>\r\n<p>The practice of paying yourself for the various roles you play in the business also plays a critical role in your future hiring activity. By paying attention to the various roles you play now, and thinking about how you would compensate for them, you will have a better idea of which roles you may want to pay someone else to do - and what pay rate you can offer them.</p>\r\n<p>Review your current P&amp;L statement this week to make sure it reflects the various roles you play in the business and how much you should be paid for doing that work. While your accountant may expect it to be set up differently, insist on having what you need to plan and run your business. Review the presentation from the first teleconference for additional tips. Ask questions and share your learns with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Strategies blog</a>Â on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-07-14', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(85, 'Money Can Be Expensive', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">Money often costs too much.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Ralph Waldo Emerson</p>\r\n<p>In our first teleconference, we discussed the wide range of options available to small business owners to finance their businesses. We cautioned, however, that each of these vehicles should be carefully reviewed and considered.</p>\r\n<p>In nearly every case, you will be required to demonstrate to your backers (whether they are governmental agencies, banks, credit unions, angel investors, or family and friends) that your business operations and plans are fundamentally sound and that there is a reasonable chance of that you will be able to pay them back, often with interest or other consideration. In general, the more you seek to borrow, the better your track record and plans need to be. Similarly, the shakier your fundamentals, the more you are likely to be asked to pay for the privilege of getting the additional money. As Emerson suggests, sometimes the costs of financing alone may be too high and ultimately sink your fledgling business.</p>\r\n<p>Too often, small business owners seek outside financing as a &quot;quick fix&quot; for operational deficiencies, poor planning, or other business deficits which would otherwise reveal a serious problem in the foundational aspects of their business and their own business acumen. In our experience, more than 90% of businesses seeking monies under these circumstances dig themselves into deep holes without achieving the results they expect. Many fail or are forced to sell at bargain prices.</p>\r\n<p>Before you leap into the financing game, make time to take stock of your business and your capabilities as a business person. Be sure you have sufficient profit and a high probability business model. Only then should you proceed. As a first step, get blank copies of application forms for the types of loans or financing you are interested in, and try filling them out. Notice where your gaps are likely be in the eyes of a lender, and identify how you can remedy them as part of your business growth plan. Review the presentation from the first teleconference for additional tips. Ask questions and share your learns with me on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach StrategiesÂ </a>blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-07-21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(86, 'Make Your Vision a Reality', ' Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p>I dream, I test my dreams against my beliefs, I dare to take risks, and I execute my vision to make those dreams come true.<br />\r\n  ~ Walt Disney</p>\r\n<p>Many know Walt Disney as a &quot;dreamer,&quot; an innovator, a visionary. But he did more than that: he tested his dreams, took risks, made plans, and executed them to make his vision become a reality. Already an accomplished actor, director, and producer, in the late 1940s Disney drew up plans for an amusement park outside of his Southern California studio where his employees could spend time with their children. He wanted to create something that looked &quot;like nothing else in the world.&quot; He spent five years developing his plan and getting financing (mortgaging everything he had), and opened Disneyland in 1955. While opening day was a disaster, more than 14 million people a year now visit his well-planned &quot;dream,&quot; and his company generated nearly $38 billion in revenue in 2008.</p>\r\n<p>What plans have you put in place to make your dreams come true? What have you done to execute those plans? What risks have you taken - and will you still need to take -- to make your vision a reality? List 2-3 actions you will take this week to move yourself forward on your plans. Identify the risks you will take. Tell your allies, so they can support you. Ask questions and share your learns with me on the Growth Coach Strategies blog on the Forum of the Business Accelerator Program website.</p>', '', '', '2009-07-28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(87, 'How a Marketing Calendar Can Help Your Business Grow ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith Marketing Coach', '<p>Over the next five months, you''ll be hearing about a number of marketing ideas which could be very helpful in growing your business. But like any entrepreneur, time steals the best ideas as daily demands of the business take precedent to the best intentions. That''s why creating a marketing calendar can be just as important as determining a marketing budget.</p>\r\n<p>Now you may be thinking, &quot;great . . . one more task to add to my list.&quot; But this little tip will only take a few minutes, and will help you stay on track and make sure you follow-through on the best ideas to grow your business.</p>\r\n<p>The first thing you need to do is prioritize your list of marketing activities that you want to accomplish this year. Since strategy should be the foundation of your marketing plan, it will dictate which marketing ideas fit your chosen strategy. Your budget will also determine which marketing activities are affordable and thus possible. Together, strategic fit and budget will help determine which ideas stay on the list and which ones fall off. Take note: we''ll be discussing a plethora of marketing tactics on Teleconference #5.</p>\r\n<p>Once you''ve prioritized your marketing activities, developing a marketing calendar is actually quite simple to do, even if you already have a marketing plan in place. Get started by making two lists: those activities that are totally new to your company and those current marketing activities that you want to improve or do better. Again, each list should be prioritized with the most important actions on top. Then, simply place each activity on your yearly business planner on the date you want to start working on their implementation. Make sure you''re not too aggressive. Remember, the old adage applies here: it''s better to do a few marketing activities well then a lot of them poorly.</p>\r\n<p align="center">Drive thy business or it will drive thee</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Benjamin Franklin</p>', '', '', '2009-06-02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(88, 'Live Your Dreams ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">&quot;Go confidently in the direction of your dreams! Live the life you''ve imagined. As you simplify your life, the laws of the universe will be simpler.&quot;</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Henry David Thoreau</p>\r\n<p>Being an entrepreneur gives you the opportunity to chase your dreams, create your reality, and take charge of your life.</p>\r\n<p>Having a compelling dream and vision will empower you to meet daily activity goals and face the challenges that will stretch - and ultimately transform-you. Every dial, every conversation, every meeting, every proposal, every sale becomes another step on the journey toward achieving your goals and fulfilling your purpose.</p>\r\n<p>What is your higher purpose for being a small business owner? Why are you in business? What is your higher value? What matters most to you? Write down your answers and keep them close at hand. Share them with your business partners, allies, and friends. Remind yourself of them when you pick up the phone, when you face rejection, when you squeeze in another sales dial on the way to pick up the kids. Ask others about their purpose and values. Share your story with other program participants online in theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Forum.</a></p>', '', '', '2009-06-09', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(89, 'Enlist Allies ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">It is probably not love that makes the world go around, but rather those mutually supportive alliances through which partners recognize their dependence on each other for the achievement of shared and private goals.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Fred Allen</p>\r\n<p>As an entrepreneur, it''s easy to feel alone. Many of us broke away from larger businesses because we had a vision of things could be done differently, of new products and services that would benefit our communities, of creating a different work environment. We were excited to forge a new path, try something new, be a pioneer. But we sometimes leave behind the support system that we had in our previous job - the people upon whom we relied to listen to our ideas, laugh at our jokes, empathize with our upsets. Even when we don'';t break away completely, those who once supported us may not be fully &quot;on board&quot; with our new direction or be able to offer us the kind of support and resources we need now.</p>\r\n<p>&quot;Friends&quot; may support us when things are going well or when they completely agree with everything we are doing, but real allies stick with us through it all. They are willing to hold a bigger vision for us than we can for ourselves, to tell us the truth when we don''t want to hear it, and to take risks in their own life in a way that is an inspiring model for us.</p>\r\n<p>Build your network of allies. Enlist at least two people to join you in this Business Accelerator Program - partners, employees, fellow small business owners, allies. Talk about what you want from the program and from them. Set up regular times to talk and meet. List the goals on which you will support each other. Share your stories on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Forum</a>.</p>', '', '', '2009-06-16', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(90, 'Take One Step ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">A journey of a thousand miles begins with a small step.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Lao Tzu (570-490 BC)</p>\r\n<p>Entrepreneurs face new challenges every day. Overdue payments, materials that don''t arrive on time, employees who don''t show up for work, ads published with typos, anxious creditors, sales prospects who don''t call back. It is easy to feel daunted and become paralyzed. To want to bail out and take what seems like a &quot;safer&quot; route to making a living.</p>\r\n<p>Often, just taking one small step in the right direction will get things moving again. Picking up the phone and making another sales call or two, talking to a vendor or creditor, placing a free job ad online, talking to an business ally or friend - anything can work.</p>\r\n<p>Today, take one small step - or several - in the direction of your dreams. While you''re at it, write down a few more that you can do tomorrow or the next day when you feel stuck. In theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Forum</a>, share with others what you did to get &quot;un-stuck,&quot; and celebrate taking another small step on your journey.</p>', '', '', '2009-06-23', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(91, 'Make Your Vision a Reality ', 'Dr. Bob Wright, Strategies Coach CEO, The Wright Business Institute', '<p align="center">Good order is the foundation of all good things.</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Edmund Burke</p>\r\n<p>Small business owners are fire-fighters by trade -- putting out the current fire that is consuming their attention. Ask any small business professional about their systems, metrics, or monitoring, and they will often tell you that they will get to it &quot;after x, y, or z&quot; is over. But whether you''ve been in your business for one week or one year, you'';ve probably realized that there is always another fire and another demand for attention. There will constantly be things pushing out the time when you''ll get your foundation set up.</p>\r\n<p>Remember, though, that even paying the most basic attention to establishing vital systems and monitors can pay off exponentially both now and in the future, in terms of resources, attention, focus, and revenue. Start with the things you need right away - whether it''s a system for filing your paperwork, a spreadsheet to track your orders, a standard invoice template, or an easily updatable to-do list. If you are a larger entity, it may be selecting and implementing a state-of-the-art accounting or CRM system, establishing a replicable hiring process, or developing an in-house training program.</p>\r\n<p>What is one foundational system or monitor you can put in place starting this week? Don''t worry about making it perfect. Any small move can make a big difference down the road. Pick one thing you''ll implement this week, and let others know so that you have support in making it a reality. Tell your colleagues about it on theÂ <a href="http://www.amfambusinessaccelerator.com/AmFamForum/index.php">Growth Coach Forum</a>Â - and pick up another idea or two while you''re there.</p>', '', '', '2009-06-30', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(92, 'A Pinch of This, a Dash of That ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith Marketing Coach', '<p>It''s tempting to try a little bit of every type of advertising that''s offered to you. Magazines, local newspapers, industry association sponsorships, event sponsorships, radio, cable, yellow pages, online ads and on and on . . .</p>\r\n<p>But with limited budgets, entrepreneurs end up with a tiny presence in each. Instead, select a few mediums that really reach your target audience and that you can afford to establish a presence in using frequency and larger visuals.</p>\r\n<p>Take a few minutes to determine exactly what your best customer looks like. If you sell to consumers, what''s her age, education, social patterns, residence, etc.? If you sell to businesses, what type of business, how old, how large?</p>\r\n<p>Now imagine yourself in your customer''s shoes. What are the most influential sources of information that influence you? List them, 1 through 5. Take a moment to explore the advertising opportunities that surround those influences. For instance, if a major influence is a trade association, perhaps advertising in the weekly e-newsletter may be very effective. Begin researching the costs and then layout a possible schedule.</p>\r\n<p>Make sure you don''t put all your eggs in one basket. Pick at least three mediums and convey a consistent message among all three. Plan your budget so you can invest enough in each one of them to make an impact.</p>\r\n<p align="center">Drive thy business or it will drive thee ~ Benjamin Franklin</p>', '', '', '2009-05-22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(93, 'What''s Love Got to Do with It? ', 'Michelle Lanter Smith Marketing Coach', '<p>Whether you''re a small business or a large national brand, good &quot;word-of-mouth&quot; is a gift of manna from the marketing gods. It''s extremely effective and it''s free. When it comes down to it, there are only two ways you can get your message out there: 1) you can pay for it, or 2) a fan of yours can rave about you.</p>\r\n<p>Word-of-mouth marketing is rather a simple concept-build an army of fans who are head-over-heels in love with you. Sounds easy, but it''s not always a simple tactic to execute. For word-of-mouth marketing to keep working over time, you have to keep the romance alive with your fans and keep them gushing on and on about you.</p>\r\n<p>So how do you spark the love? How do you stimulate word-of-mouth? First, you have to give people a reason to talk. Brainstorm ideas that you could implement in your firm that are bit &quot;out of the box&quot; or exceed people''s expectations. Take the Internet shoe phenomenon, Zappos. They pay for the return shipping on the shoes that you''ve ordered and don''t like. For any woman that loves her shoes, that''s extremely cool . . . that means you can order as many shoes as you like and return them, without penalty! Now that''s something to talk about.</p>\r\n<p>Let''s look at how a local janitorial service could stimulate word of mouth. If the customer expects that you''ll clean the basics-vacuuming, mopping, dusting, sanitizing. How about placing a bouquet of flowers in the lobby to add a fresh fragrance? This doesn''t cost you much, but from a customer''s perspective, it''s really something to talk about.</p>\r\n<p>The second key aspect of word-of-mouth marketing is that you have to make it easy for the conversation to take place. In other words, you have to enable the message to be shared. Don''t expect people to repeat your very carefully crafted brand message; instead, they''ll repeat what they love about you . . . in their own words. The best, most effective tool out there right now is e-mail. Send your message in e-mails to your fan. It''s such an easy and affordable step for you to take and it makes it very simple for your fans to then spread your word. Also be sure to consider some of the new tools for social interaction: Facebook and Twitter. After a customer completes an electronic survey or signs up for an e-newsletter, ask &quot;do you want to be my fan on Facebook? &quot;Instantly, your Facebook presence grows and so too does your opportunity to amplify your message across your marketplace.</p>\r\n<p align="center">Drive thy business or it will drive thee</p>\r\n<p align="center">~ Benjamin Franklin</p>', '', '', '2009-05-22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(94, 'Make Objections Work for You ', 'Roula Crews, Sales Coach, President, Hi-Impact Marketing & Sales Solutions, Inc. ', '<p>&ldquo;Every sales has five basic obstacles: no need, no money, no hurry, no desire and no trust.&rdquo;&nbsp; Zig Ziglar</p>\r\n<p>Early in sales, I learned that I would encounter a variety of objections prior to making a sale.&nbsp; It was as though every sale had a mountain to be climbed, a race to be won.&nbsp; What I also learned was that when I didn''t get any objections, I probably wasn''t going to get the sale either; I was just having a conversation with the customer.</p>\r\n<p>What exactly is an objection?&nbsp; The dictionary describes it as "an expression of opposition or disapproval."&nbsp; I describe an objection, in the sales process, as a genuine interest to do business with you.&nbsp; So what you might consider to be an objection isn''t really an objection at all, but a simple expression of concern on the part of the customer.</p>\r\n<p>For example, a customer may be concerned that your price is too high, or your delivery is too long, or the specifications might not meet his needs, or he&rsquo;s happy with his current supplier.&nbsp; It''s the job of the salesperson to convince the customer of the value of your product and service.&nbsp; Also, by providing testimonials and demonstrating how your quality and delivery has repeatedly met the demands of your current customers, you can build comfort in their decision to switch vendors.</p>\r\n<p>So, what''s the secret to handling objections?&nbsp; The secret is to manage the sales process so as to answer any potential objections that could arise.&nbsp; First, people buy from people they like and trust.&nbsp; So build rapport, be likeable and be trustworthy.&nbsp; Come through on promises that you make.&nbsp; Secondly, listen to your customer''s concerns and read their body language.&nbsp; Be perceptive as to why they are hesitating or what concerns they have.&nbsp; Third, ask questions, probing and qualifying the customer throughout the process.&nbsp; Identify what situations are of importance and how to solve any concerns that may be standing in the way of them buying from you.&nbsp; Lastly, ask for the sale; for example, "Mr. Customer, if I can guarantee that we can provide you with this product by next week, may we proceed today?"</p>\r\n<p><strong>Overcoming Sales Objections - Five Tips on what NOT to do</strong><br />While many salespeople hate hearing &ldquo;No&rdquo; from the prospect, the good ones know that a negative response is just another opportunity to close the sale.&nbsp; Here are five things NOT to do that will help you win the sale.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t argue</strong><br />You won&rsquo;t win even if you&rsquo;re right, and you&rsquo;ll probably lose the sale.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Make sure you understand the objection</strong><br />If you&rsquo;re not sure why your client is objecting or hesitating, don&rsquo;t start trying to address the issue. Probe a little deeper and make sure you know what the real objection is and then address that.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t avoid the issue</strong><br />Sometimes the prospect&rsquo;s negative reaction will be more emotion-based instead of factual. The worst thing you can do is try to avoid the feeling that is being expressed. Let the prospect vent a little and then address the issue.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t guess at the answer</strong><br />If you can&rsquo;t answer the prospect&rsquo;s question or objection, don&rsquo;t guess.&nbsp; Instead, admit you don''t know and assure the prospect you&rsquo;ll find the answer. Getting back to the prospect demonstrates that you follow through on your commitments.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t dwell too long on an objection</strong><br />When faced with a sales objection, don&rsquo;t dwell too long on it--address it and move on.&nbsp; Your answer should be just long enough to satisfy the prospect and no longer!<br />None of this is magic; in fact, a lot of it is common sense.&nbsp; Remember these <strong>Don&rsquo;ts</strong> and you&rsquo;re going to hear <strong>Yes</strong> a lot more often!</p>\r\n<p>The information contained in this article is intended to be general in nature and may not apply to your situation.&nbsp; Before any action is taken based upon this information, legal counsel should be consulted.</p>', '', '', '2012-03-27', '2012-06-04 00:12:53');
